"use strict";(globalThis.webpackChunkarpit_blog=globalThis.webpackChunkarpit_blog||[]).push([[8130],{7735(e){e.exports=JSON.parse('{"archive":{"blogPosts":[{"id":"safe-media-migration-ai","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/safe-media-migration-ai","editUrl":"https://github.com/yesarpit/yesarpit.github.io/edit/main/blog/2026-04-19-safe-media-migration-ai.md","source":"@site/blog/2026-04-19-safe-media-migration-ai.md","title":"Reclaiming 50GB+ Mac Storage Safely: A Journey from \'Disk Full\' to AI-Powered Deduping","description":"Insights on engineering leadership, decision-making under pressure, and scaling high-performance technical teams.","date":"2026-04-19T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"productivity","permalink":"/blog/tags/productivity"},{"inline":true,"label":"macos","permalink":"/blog/tags/macos"},{"inline":true,"label":"ai","permalink":"/blog/tags/ai"},{"inline":true,"label":"python","permalink":"/blog/tags/python"},{"inline":true,"label":"storage","permalink":"/blog/tags/storage"}],"readingTime":2.96,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Arpit Sharma","title":"Maintainer of this blog","url":"https://yesarpit.github.io","imageURL":"https://github.com/yesarpit.png","key":"arpit","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"safe-media-migration-ai","title":"Reclaiming 50GB+ Mac Storage Safely: A Journey from \'Disk Full\' to AI-Powered Deduping","authors":["arpit"],"tags":["productivity","macos","ai","python","storage"],"description":"Insights on engineering leadership, decision-making under pressure, and scaling high-performance technical teams."},"unlisted":false,"nextItem":{"title":"Lessons I Am Trying Not to Forget","permalink":"/blog/lessons-i-am-trying-not-to-forget"}},"content":"We\'ve all been there: the dreaded **\\"Your disk is almost full\\"** notification on macOS. This week, I hit the wall. A 52GB folder of mobile backups, photos, and videos was choking my internal SSD. \\n\\nBut as an engineer, the thought of manually dragging-and-dropping thousands of files\u2014or worse, manually deleting duplicates\u2014felt like a recipe for disaster. One wrong click and a decade of memories could be gone.\\n\\nHere is how I solved it using a \\"Safety-First\\" framework and a custom Python deduplication engine.\\n\\n\x3c!-- truncate --\x3e\\n\\n## The Problem: Data Hoarding & The NTFS Wall\\n\\nI had a massive archive of media to move to my reliable **Seagate Backup Plus**. But I faced three major hurdles:\\n\\n1.  **The Risk of Loss**: Drag-and-drop in Finder is \\"silent.\\" If it fails halfway, you don\'t know what\'s copied and what\'s not.\\n2.  **The NTFS Wall**: My Seagate drive was formatted in NTFS (Windows standard), making it **Read-Only** on my Mac. I couldn\'t write a single byte to it.\\n3.  **The Duplicate Nightmare**: Over years of backups, I had hundreds of duplicate files with different names (e.g., `IMG_123.jpg` vs `IMG_123_copy.jpg`).\\n\\n## Attempt 1: The Manual Way (and why I didn\'t do it)\\nManual deletion is the enemy of accuracy. I considered online \\"Duplicate Finder\\" tools, but I didn\'t want to grant a random app access to my entire photo library, nor did I want to pay $20 for a one-time cleanup.\\n\\n## The Solution: AI-Guided \\"Safety-First\\" Migration\\n\\nI decided to pair-program the solution with my AI coding agent. We broke the process into 100% safe checkpoints.\\n\\n### Phase 1: Overcoming the NTFS Barrier\\nBefore moving data, I had to fix the \\"Read-Only\\" status. Guided by the AI, I installed a professional NTFS driver (Paragon). After a quick reboot and some permission juggling, my Seagate was finally writable.\\n\\n### Phase 2: The \\"Immutable\\" Copy (Rsync)\\nInstead of a simple copy, we used `rsync`. \\n```bash\\nrsync -avh --progress --ignore-existing \\"[Source]\\" \\"[Destination]\\"\\n```\\n**Why?** Because `rsync` is resumable. If my Mac crashed during the 52GB transfer, I could just run it again, and it would pick up exactly where it left off, skipping everything already safe on the drive.\\n\\n### Phase 3: The \\"Fingerprinting\\" Logic (The \'Magic\' Part)\\nOnce the data was safely on the Seagate, I wanted to remove duplicates. This is where the AI suggested something far superior to filename checking: **SHA-256 Hashing.**\\n\\n#### The Logic Behind the Scenes:\\n1.  **Size Grouping**: The script first groups files by their size. If two files are different sizes, they *cannot* be the same.\\n2.  **Cryptographic Fingerprinting**: For files with the same size, the script generates a unique SHA-256 \\"Hash\\" (a digital fingerprint).\\n3.  **O(1) Lookup**: Using a Python dictionary (Hashmap), we can check if we\'ve seen that exact fingerprint before in constant time.\\n\\nIf the fingerprints match, the data is 100% identical byte-for-byte, regardless of the filename.\\n\\n## The Results\\n*   **Space Saved**: **52GB** instantly reclaimed on my Mac.\\n*   **Accuracy**: 100%. We verified the file counts and total bytes using `find` and `du`.\\n*   **Time Invested**: About 10 minutes of setup for a process that would have taken hours of manual sorting.\\n*   **Cost**: $0 ($20 saved on premium deduplication apps).\\n\\n## Conclusion\\nThis journey reminded me that coding isn\'t just for building products; it\'s a productivity superpower for our daily lives. By automating the \\"boring\\" and \\"risky\\" parts of file management with AI, I moved from a panicked \\"Disk Full\\" state to a perfectly organized, deduplicated archive in a single afternoon.\\n\\n**Safe moving, safe coding!**"},{"id":"lessons-i-am-trying-not-to-forget","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/lessons-i-am-trying-not-to-forget","editUrl":"https://github.com/yesarpit/yesarpit.github.io/edit/main/blog/2026-03-18-lessons-i-am-trying-not-to-forget.md","source":"@site/blog/2026-03-18-lessons-i-am-trying-not-to-forget.md","title":"Lessons I Am Trying Not to Forget","description":"Insights on engineering leadership, decision-making under pressure, and scaling high-performance technical teams.","date":"2026-03-18T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"life-skills","permalink":"/blog/tags/life-skills"},{"inline":true,"label":"leadership","permalink":"/blog/tags/leadership"},{"inline":true,"label":"executive-lessons","permalink":"/blog/tags/executive-lessons"}],"readingTime":1.83,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Arpit Sharma","title":"Maintainer of this blog","url":"https://yesarpit.github.io","imageURL":"https://github.com/yesarpit.png","key":"arpit","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"lessons-i-am-trying-not-to-forget","title":"Lessons I Am Trying Not to Forget","authors":["arpit"],"tags":["life-skills","leadership","executive-lessons"],"description":"Insights on engineering leadership, decision-making under pressure, and scaling high-performance technical teams."},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Reclaiming 50GB+ Mac Storage Safely: A Journey from \'Disk Full\' to AI-Powered Deduping","permalink":"/blog/safe-media-migration-ai"},"nextItem":{"title":"Memos I Wish More Leaders Wrote","permalink":"/blog/memos-i-wish-more-leaders-wrote"}},"content":"### Read This\\n\\nNot every post needs to be a framework.\\n\\nSome posts are better as reminders.\\n\\nThis is one of those.\\n\\nA few things I keep relearning, and apparently keep needing to relearn.\\n\\n\x3c!-- truncate --\x3e\\n\\n___\\n\\n### 1) Clarity saves more energy than intensity\\n\\nWhen things get messy, people often respond with more urgency.\\n\\nSometimes what is actually needed is more clarity.\\n\\nIntensity without clarity creates noise.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### 2) Smart people also need simple communication\\n\\nI used to think strong teams need more complexity because they can handle it.\\n\\nNot always.\\n\\nStrong teams move better when message is clean, not when it sounds sophisticated.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### 3) Some problems shrink when named properly\\n\\nA lot of stress comes from vague discomfort.\\n\\nThe moment you can say:\\n\\nthis is an ownership issue  \\nthis is a trust issue  \\nthis is a sequencing issue  \\n\\nthings start becoming easier to deal with.\\n\\nNaming does not solve the issue fully.\\nBut it reduces fog.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### 4) You can outgrow environments quietly\\n\\nNot with drama.\\nNot with anger.\\n\\nSometimes a place simply stops stretching you.\\nOr your values stop matching the way work is done.\\n\\nThat is useful to notice early.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### 5) What feels urgent is not always important\\n\\nThis lesson keeps coming back forever.\\n\\nInbox urgency is seductive.\\nReaction feels productive.\\n\\nBut a lot of meaningful progress still comes from fewer, deeper, more deliberate moves.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### 6) Strong people also get tired in invisible ways\\n\\nThis one is important.\\n\\nA person can keep delivering and still be draining internally.\\n\\nSo not all burnout announces itself loudly.\\nSometimes it shows up as reduced joy, reduced sharpness, reduced care.\\n\\nThat needs attention too.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### 7) A good reputation is built in repeated ordinary moments\\n\\nNot only big wins.\\n\\nIt is built in:\\n\\n* how you respond under pressure\\n* whether people can rely on your word\\n* how you treat others when nothing is in it for you\\n* how you handle disagreement\\n\\nThese ordinary moments compound.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### Final thought\\n\\nI like big frameworks.\\nBut sometimes what helps most is a smaller list you can return to when life gets noisy.\\n\\nThis is one of those lists for me.\\n\\nMaybe I will need to read it again later too."},{"id":"memos-i-wish-more-leaders-wrote","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/memos-i-wish-more-leaders-wrote","editUrl":"https://github.com/yesarpit/yesarpit.github.io/edit/main/blog/2026-02-06-memos-i-wish-more-leaders-wrote.md","source":"@site/blog/2026-02-06-memos-i-wish-more-leaders-wrote.md","title":"Memos I Wish More Leaders Wrote","description":"Insights on engineering leadership, decision-making under pressure, and scaling high-performance technical teams.","date":"2026-02-06T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"leadership","permalink":"/blog/tags/leadership"},{"inline":true,"label":"executive-lessons","permalink":"/blog/tags/executive-lessons"},{"inline":true,"label":"communication","permalink":"/blog/tags/communication"}],"readingTime":1.68,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Arpit Sharma","title":"Maintainer of this blog","url":"https://yesarpit.github.io","imageURL":"https://github.com/yesarpit.png","key":"arpit","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"memos-i-wish-more-leaders-wrote","title":"Memos I Wish More Leaders Wrote","authors":["arpit"],"tags":["leadership","executive-lessons","communication"],"description":"Insights on engineering leadership, decision-making under pressure, and scaling high-performance technical teams."},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Lessons I Am Trying Not to Forget","permalink":"/blog/lessons-i-am-trying-not-to-forget"},"nextItem":{"title":"Career Decisions Compound Quietly","permalink":"/blog/career-decisions-compound-quietly"}},"content":"### Read This\\n\\nI think many teams would become healthier if leaders wrote more honest memos.\\n\\nNot longer memos.\\nNot more polished memos.\\n\\nJust more real ones.\\n\\nSo this post is in that spirit.\\n\\nBelow are 5 memos I wish more leaders wrote, or at least communicated this clearly.\\n\\n\x3c!-- truncate --\x3e\\n\\n___\\n\\n### Memo 1\\n\\nWe are doing too many things.\\n\\nSo even though everyone is busy, progress feels thinner than it should.\\n\\nThis is not a motivation problem.\\nIt is a focus problem.\\n\\nWe need to choose fewer priorities and defend them harder.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### Memo 2\\n\\nSome of our delays are not execution delays.\\nThey are decision delays.\\n\\nWe are waiting too long to clarify ownership, trade-offs, and direction.\\n\\nThat makes teams look slower than they really are.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### Memo 3\\n\\nWe say we want ownership, but sometimes we still punish people for acting without too much permission.\\n\\nThat contradiction confuses teams.\\n\\nIf we want ownership, then we also need to tolerate thoughtful initiative.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### Memo 4\\n\\nSome meetings exist because trust is low.\\n\\nThat is uncomfortable, but true.\\n\\nWhen leaders do not trust teams, they create extra layers of reviews, updates, and approvals.\\n\\nThen everybody complains about bureaucracy.\\n\\nSometimes bureaucracy is just mistrust with calendar invites.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### Memo 5\\n\\nA lot of what we call \u201cleadership communication\u201d is too abstract.\\n\\nTeams do not only need inspiration.\\nThey also need plain clarity:\\n\\n* what matters most\\n* what changed\\n* what trade-off we made\\n* what we are no longer prioritizing\\n\\nThat kind of clarity is respect.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### Why I like memo-style thinking\\n\\nBecause memos remove some theatre.\\n\\nThey force sharper thought.\\n\\nYou cannot hide weak thinking as easily when you have to write it clearly.\\n\\nAnd maybe that is why I wish more leaders used them better.\\n\\nNot to sound important.\\nTo reduce confusion.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### Final thought\\n\\nIf more leadership communication felt like a useful internal memo and less like a polished announcement, teams would probably trust it more.\\n\\nAnd honestly, they would probably understand it better too."},{"id":"career-decisions-compound-quietly","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/career-decisions-compound-quietly","editUrl":"https://github.com/yesarpit/yesarpit.github.io/edit/main/blog/2025-12-03-career-decisions-compound-quietly.md","source":"@site/blog/2025-12-03-career-decisions-compound-quietly.md","title":"Career Decisions Compound Quietly","description":"Insights on engineering leadership, decision-making under pressure, and scaling high-performance technical teams.","date":"2025-12-03T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"life-skills","permalink":"/blog/tags/life-skills"},{"inline":true,"label":"career","permalink":"/blog/tags/career"},{"inline":true,"label":"leadership","permalink":"/blog/tags/leadership"}],"readingTime":2.67,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Arpit Sharma","title":"Maintainer of this blog","url":"https://yesarpit.github.io","imageURL":"https://github.com/yesarpit.png","key":"arpit","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"career-decisions-compound-quietly","title":"Career Decisions Compound Quietly","authors":["arpit"],"tags":["life-skills","career","leadership"],"description":"Insights on engineering leadership, decision-making under pressure, and scaling high-performance technical teams."},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Memos I Wish More Leaders Wrote","permalink":"/blog/memos-i-wish-more-leaders-wrote"},"nextItem":{"title":"Executive Presence Without Theater","permalink":"/blog/executive-presence-without-theater"}},"content":"### Read This\\n\\nMost people notice career growth only when something visible happens.\\n\\nPromotion.\\nBig title.\\nBig company.\\nComp jump.\\n\\nBut a lot of career trajectory gets shaped much earlier and much more quietly.\\n\\nBy decisions that do not look dramatic at the time.\\n\\nThat is why I think career decisions compound quietly.\\n\\nAnd because they compound, small repeated choices matter more than people think.\\n\\n\x3c!-- truncate --\x3e\\n\\n___\\n\\n### What kind of choices am I talking about?\\n\\nThings like:\\n\\n* what kind of problems you choose\\n* what kind of people you work with\\n* whether you choose visibility or comfort\\n* whether you build depth or only chase titles\\n* whether you leave when learning stops\\n\\nThese choices dont always give instant reward.\\n\\nBut over years, they stack.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### Compounding in career is strange\\n\\nIn money, compounding is easier to notice.\\n\\nIn career, it is slower and less visible.\\n\\nYou may not see the value immediately when you:\\n\\n* choose a harder role\\n* learn a harder system\\n* work under a strong manager\\n* stay with discomfort long enough to grow\\n\\nBut those things build judgment.\\nAnd judgment compounds.\\n\\nLater it starts showing up as:\\n\\n* better decisions\\n* stronger opportunities\\n* more trust\\n* larger scope\\n* clearer self-awareness\\n\\n___\\n\\n### Short-term comfort can be expensive\\n\\nThis is one of the hardest lessons.\\n\\nComfort is not always bad.\\nBut too much comfort creates hidden stagnation.\\n\\nIf a role gives:\\n\\n* predictable days\\n* low challenge\\n* no stretch\\n* no new skill pressure\\n\\nit may feel peaceful.\\n\\nBut if you stay there too long, the cost is not visible immediately.\\nThe cost appears later as reduced growth slope.\\n\\nThat is why some easy decisions become expensive only after years.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### The people around you matter a lot\\n\\nThis one compounds very strongly.\\n\\nIf you keep working with people who:\\n\\n* think clearly\\n* raise your standards\\n* challenge your assumptions\\n* operate with ownership\\n\\nthen your own quality rises over time.\\n\\nAnd if you spend years in low-ownership environments, that also leaves a mark.\\n\\nPeople often underestimate this because it does not show up as bullet point on resume.\\nBut it absolutely shapes the person behind the resume.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### Titles are useful, but not enough\\n\\nA lot of people optimize too directly for title.\\n\\nI understand why.\\nTitles matter.\\n\\nBut title without capability is fragile.\\n\\nAnd capability built in the right environments tends to produce title anyway, eventually.\\n\\nSo I usually think the better question is:\\n\\nam I becoming stronger in a way that compounds?\\n\\nThat includes:\\n\\n* judgment\\n* communication\\n* ownership\\n* technical depth\\n* leadership maturity\\n\\nThese are slow assets.\\nBut they travel well.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### What I would apply\\n\\nPractical version:\\n\\n1. choose learning slope over short-term comfort more often\\n2. work with people who sharpen your standards\\n3. optimize for capability, not only title\\n4. notice where you are coasting too long\\n5. remember that repeated small choices shape long-term trajectory\\n\\nYou do not need dramatic reinvention every year.\\nSometimes you just need better repeated decisions.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### Final thought\\n\\nCareer rarely changes only because of one big move.\\n\\nUsually it changes because of dozens of smaller choices that looked ordinary when you made them.\\n\\nThat is what makes compounding so powerful.\\n\\nIt is quiet at first.\\nThen one day people call it trajectory."},{"id":"executive-presence-without-theater","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/executive-presence-without-theater","editUrl":"https://github.com/yesarpit/yesarpit.github.io/edit/main/blog/2025-07-15-executive-presence-without-theater.md","source":"@site/blog/2025-07-15-executive-presence-without-theater.md","title":"Executive Presence Without Theater","description":"Insights on engineering leadership, decision-making under pressure, and scaling high-performance technical teams.","date":"2025-07-15T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"leadership","permalink":"/blog/tags/leadership"},{"inline":true,"label":"executive-lessons","permalink":"/blog/tags/executive-lessons"},{"inline":true,"label":"communication","permalink":"/blog/tags/communication"}],"readingTime":2.44,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Arpit Sharma","title":"Maintainer of this blog","url":"https://yesarpit.github.io","imageURL":"https://github.com/yesarpit.png","key":"arpit","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"executive-presence-without-theater","title":"Executive Presence Without Theater","authors":["arpit"],"tags":["leadership","executive-lessons","communication"],"description":"Insights on engineering leadership, decision-making under pressure, and scaling high-performance technical teams."},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Career Decisions Compound Quietly","permalink":"/blog/career-decisions-compound-quietly"},"nextItem":{"title":"The Cost of Being the Smartest Person in the Room","permalink":"/blog/the-cost-of-being-the-smartest-person-in-the-room"}},"content":"### Read This\\n\\nExecutive presence is one of those phrases that sounds useful and annoying at the same time.\\n\\nUseful because it matters.\\nAnnoying because many people turn it into performance art.\\n\\nI think the cleaner way to see it is this:\\n\\n**executive presence is not about sounding important, it is about creating confidence under pressure**\\n\\nThat is very different.\\n\\n\x3c!-- truncate --\x3e\\n\\n___\\n\\n### What people usually get wrong\\n\\nThey think executive presence means:\\n\\n* polished words\\n* slow voice\\n* serious expression\\n* fancy slides\\n* zero visible uncertainty\\n\\nThat is mostly theatre.\\n\\nIt may impress for few minutes.\\nIt does not hold up when situation becomes hard.\\n\\nReal executive presence shows up more clearly when:\\n\\n* things are messy\\n* leaders disagree\\n* stakes are high\\n* pressure is visible\\n\\nThen people notice who brings clarity and calm.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### Presence is really about signal quality\\n\\nWhen senior leaders speak, people are not only hearing content.\\nThey are reading signal.\\n\\nSignal like:\\n\\n* do you understand the problem?\\n* do you understand the trade-off?\\n* can you simplify without oversimplifying?\\n* can you stay steady without becoming robotic?\\n\\nThis is why some people sound senior even with simple language.\\nAnd some people sound complicated without sounding trustworthy.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### Calm is underrated\\n\\nNot fake calm.\\nReal calm.\\n\\nThere is a big difference.\\n\\nFake calm hides uncertainty.\\nReal calm holds uncertainty without spreading panic.\\n\\nThat matters a lot in leadership.\\n\\nBecause teams often borrow emotional signal from leaders.\\n\\nIf leader becomes scattered, urgency spreads badly.\\nIf leader becomes grounded, thinking improves.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### Clarity matters more than polish\\n\\nI have seen leaders use sophisticated language and still leave room confused.\\n\\nAnd I have seen others speak very simply and move entire room forward.\\n\\nWhy?\\n\\nBecause clarity beats polish.\\n\\nAt senior levels, people respect leaders who can say:\\n\\n* here is the real issue\\n* here is what we know\\n* here is what we dont know\\n* here is the call we are making\\n\\nThat is presence.\\n\\nNot vocabulary gymnastics.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### Presence without substance collapses quickly\\n\\nThis is important.\\n\\nIf someone has style but not judgment, it becomes visible over time.\\n\\nEventually people notice:\\n\\n* meetings sound strong but direction is fuzzy\\n* communication is polished but decisions are weak\\n* confidence is high but signal quality is low\\n\\nSo I dont think executive presence should ever be separated from real competence.\\n\\nIt is not a replacement.\\nIt is a carrier.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### What I would apply\\n\\nPractical version:\\n\\n1. simplify your message before trying to strengthen your tone\\n2. do not hide uncertainty unnecessarily\\n3. bring calm, especially when pressure is high\\n4. say the actual trade-off clearly\\n5. make people leave with more clarity than they came with\\n\\nIf that is happening regularly, presence is already improving.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### Final thought\\n\\nExecutive presence becomes powerful when it stops being performance.\\n\\nFor me, the best version of it is simple:\\n\\npeople trust your presence because your clarity, judgment, and steadiness make hard situations easier to navigate.\\n\\nThat is enough.\\nNo theatre needed."},{"id":"the-cost-of-being-the-smartest-person-in-the-room","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/the-cost-of-being-the-smartest-person-in-the-room","editUrl":"https://github.com/yesarpit/yesarpit.github.io/edit/main/blog/2025-04-11-the-cost-of-being-the-smartest-person-in-the-room.md","source":"@site/blog/2025-04-11-the-cost-of-being-the-smartest-person-in-the-room.md","title":"The Cost of Being the Smartest Person in the Room","description":"Insights on engineering leadership, decision-making under pressure, and scaling high-performance technical teams.","date":"2025-04-11T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"leadership","permalink":"/blog/tags/leadership"},{"inline":true,"label":"management","permalink":"/blog/tags/management"},{"inline":true,"label":"life-skills","permalink":"/blog/tags/life-skills"}],"readingTime":2.46,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Arpit Sharma","title":"Maintainer of this blog","url":"https://yesarpit.github.io","imageURL":"https://github.com/yesarpit.png","key":"arpit","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"the-cost-of-being-the-smartest-person-in-the-room","title":"The Cost of Being the Smartest Person in the Room","authors":["arpit"],"tags":["leadership","management","life-skills"],"description":"Insights on engineering leadership, decision-making under pressure, and scaling high-performance technical teams."},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Executive Presence Without Theater","permalink":"/blog/executive-presence-without-theater"},"nextItem":{"title":"Decision Making Under Ambiguity","permalink":"/blog/decision-making-under-ambiguity"}},"content":"### Read This\\n\\nBeing smart is useful.\\n\\nBuilding a room where only your intelligence matters is not.\\n\\nA lot of leaders do this without realizing it.\\n\\nThey become the fastest thinker, quickest responder, final answer provider, and unofficial escalation endpoint for everything.\\n\\nFrom outside, it looks impressive.\\n\\nFrom inside, it creates dependency.\\n\\nAnd dependency does not scale.\\n\\n\x3c!-- truncate --\x3e\\n\\n___\\n\\n### Why this happens\\n\\nUsually not because leader is arrogant.\\n\\nOften because leader is capable.\\n\\nThey:\\n\\n* understand systems deeply\\n* move faster than others\\n* see mistakes early\\n* know how to unblock things quickly\\n\\nSo naturally the team starts relying on them more.\\n\\nThen slowly a pattern forms:\\n\\nimportant things wait for one person.\\n\\nThat is where the trouble starts.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### Intelligence can become a bottleneck\\n\\nThis is the trap.\\n\\nIf your team cannot make strong decisions without you, then your intelligence is no longer only an asset.\\nIt has become a structural dependency.\\n\\nThat shows up in many ways:\\n\\n* meetings become approval sessions\\n* senior people stop pushing their own view\\n* execution slows when you are unavailable\\n* team confidence becomes uneven\\n\\nThis is expensive.\\n\\nNot just for speed.\\nAlso for leadership pipeline.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### Strong leaders dont just solve\\n\\nThey also create more solvers.\\n\\nThat is the harder job.\\n\\nAnyone with enough experience can keep answering.\\n\\nMuch fewer people can build an environment where others start thinking with more clarity, more confidence, and more ownership.\\n\\nThat takes patience.\\nAnd ego control.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### How this shows up in meetings\\n\\nYou can usually feel it quickly.\\n\\nIf leader speaks early and strongly, the room narrows.\\n\\nPeople start optimizing for agreement.\\nNot for thought.\\n\\nThen later everybody says:\\n\\n\u201cyes makes sense\u201d\\n\\nand fewer people ask:\\n\\n\u201cwait, are we sure?\u201d\\n\\nThat is not alignment.\\nThat is silent compression of thinking.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### What good leaders do differently\\n\\nThey do not make themselves small.\\nThey make more space for good thinking.\\n\\nThat can mean:\\n\\n* asking before answering\\n* waiting before concluding\\n* letting others own the frame\\n* inviting disagreement early\\n* rewarding clarity, not only confidence\\n\\nThis is subtle work.\\nBut powerful.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### The hidden cost\\n\\nIf leader becomes central brain of the team, three things happen:\\n\\n1. scale drops\\n2. succession weakens\\n3. team maturity stalls\\n\\nThat third one matters a lot.\\n\\nBecause people dont become strong by standing near strong leaders.\\nThey become strong by carrying meaningful judgment themselves.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### What I would apply\\n\\nPractical version:\\n\\n1. speak later in important discussions\\n2. ask one more question before giving answer\\n3. let capable people own uncomfortable decisions\\n4. notice where your speed is suppressing others\\n5. measure leadership by how much strong thinking exists without you\\n\\nThat last one is the real test.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### Final thought\\n\\nThere is no special prize for being the smartest person in the room if the room becomes weaker because of it.\\n\\nAt senior levels, the real win is different.\\n\\nCan you raise the intelligence of the room itself?\\n\\nThat is much harder.\\nThat is also much more valuable."},{"id":"decision-making-under-ambiguity","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/decision-making-under-ambiguity","editUrl":"https://github.com/yesarpit/yesarpit.github.io/edit/main/blog/2025-01-17-decision-making-under-ambiguity.md","source":"@site/blog/2025-01-17-decision-making-under-ambiguity.md","title":"Decision Making Under Ambiguity","description":"Insights on engineering leadership, decision-making under pressure, and scaling high-performance technical teams.","date":"2025-01-17T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"leadership","permalink":"/blog/tags/leadership"},{"inline":true,"label":"management","permalink":"/blog/tags/management"},{"inline":true,"label":"executive-lessons","permalink":"/blog/tags/executive-lessons"}],"readingTime":2.57,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Arpit Sharma","title":"Maintainer of this blog","url":"https://yesarpit.github.io","imageURL":"https://github.com/yesarpit.png","key":"arpit","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"decision-making-under-ambiguity","title":"Decision Making Under Ambiguity","authors":["arpit"],"tags":["leadership","management","executive-lessons"],"description":"Insights on engineering leadership, decision-making under pressure, and scaling high-performance technical teams."},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"The Cost of Being the Smartest Person in the Room","permalink":"/blog/the-cost-of-being-the-smartest-person-in-the-room"},"nextItem":{"title":"What The Hard Thing About Hard Things Taught Me About Leading Through Pressure","permalink":"/blog/the-hard-thing-about-hard-things-in-engineering"}},"content":"### Read This\\n\\nA lot of people think senior leadership means having better answers.\\n\\nNot exactly.\\n\\nMany times it just means you have to decide **before** the answer becomes obvious.\\n\\nThat is the real difficulty.\\n\\nNot decision making with full clarity.\\nDecision making with partial information, limited time, strong opinions, and visible consequences.\\n\\nThat is why I think one of the most important leadership skills is this:\\n\\n**being able to move with imperfect information without becoming reckless**.\\n\\n\x3c!-- truncate --\x3e\\n\\n___\\n\\n### Why this gets harder at senior levels\\n\\nAt junior levels, many decisions are local.\\n\\nAt senior levels, decisions start carrying more weight:\\n\\n* org direction\\n* hiring quality\\n* architecture bets\\n* platform priorities\\n* reorgs\\n* roadmap trade-offs\\n\\nAnd the painful part is this:\\n\\nyou usually dont get all facts neatly arranged before making them.\\n\\nIf you wait for perfect certainty, you become slow.\\nIf you decide too fast, you become dangerous.\\n\\nSo the real game is not certainty.\\nIt is judgment.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### Most bad decisions dont come from bad intent\\n\\nThey usually come from one of these:\\n\\n* false urgency\\n* ego attachment\\n* too much optimism\\n* weak challenge from others\\n* fear of looking uncertain\\n\\nThis last one is huge.\\n\\nSome leaders rush into confidence because they think uncertainty makes them look weak.\\n\\nActually the opposite is true.\\n\\nFake certainty is much more damaging than visible thoughtful uncertainty.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### Good leaders ask better questions\\n\\nWhen things are ambiguous, I think these questions matter:\\n\\n* what do we know for sure?\\n* what are we assuming?\\n* what happens if we are wrong?\\n* is this reversible or irreversible?\\n* what is the cost of waiting?\\n\\nThat last one matters a lot.\\n\\nBecause sometimes delay looks safe, but is actually decision by avoidance.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### Reversible vs irreversible decisions\\n\\nThis is one of the cleanest frameworks.\\n\\nSome decisions are reversible.\\nYou can adjust later.\\n\\nSome are expensive to reverse.\\nThose need more thought.\\n\\nThe mistake is treating all decisions with same weight.\\n\\nThen you either:\\n\\n* over-analyze small things\\n* under-think big things\\n\\nBoth are expensive.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### Ambiguity is where leadership style gets exposed\\n\\nWhen path is clear, almost anyone can sound decisive.\\n\\nBut when:\\n\\n* data is incomplete\\n* teams disagree\\n* risks are real\\n* pressure is rising\\n\\nthen leadership quality starts becoming visible.\\n\\nDo you freeze?\\nDo you panic?\\nDo you overcontrol?\\nDo you perform confidence?\\nOr do you create enough clarity for people to move?\\n\\nThat is what people actually remember.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### What helps in real life\\n\\nPractical version:\\n\\n1. separate facts from assumptions\\n2. understand what can be reversed\\n3. ask for challenge, not only alignment\\n4. decide with conviction, but not ego attachment\\n5. revisit decisions when new signal appears\\n\\nThis is important.\\n\\nChanging your mind after new evidence is not weak leadership.\\nIt is healthy leadership.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### Final thought\\n\\nLeadership is not tested most when things are obvious.\\n\\nIt is tested when things are unclear and people still need direction.\\n\\nThat is why decision making under ambiguity matters so much.\\n\\nNot because leaders should pretend to know everything.\\nBut because teams need someone who can move thoughtfully even when the fog has not cleared yet."},{"id":"the-hard-thing-about-hard-things-in-engineering","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/the-hard-thing-about-hard-things-in-engineering","editUrl":"https://github.com/yesarpit/yesarpit.github.io/edit/main/blog/2024-11-07-the-hard-thing-about-hard-things-in-engineering.md","source":"@site/blog/2024-11-07-the-hard-thing-about-hard-things-in-engineering.md","title":"What The Hard Thing About Hard Things Taught Me About Leading Through Pressure","description":"A leadership framework for engineering executives on counterintuitive decision-making and leading through high-stakes pressure.","date":"2024-11-07T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"leadership","permalink":"/blog/tags/leadership"},{"inline":true,"label":"engineering-management","permalink":"/blog/tags/engineering-management"},{"inline":true,"label":"books","permalink":"/blog/tags/books"}],"readingTime":2.9,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Arpit Sharma","title":"Maintainer of this blog","url":"https://yesarpit.github.io","imageURL":"https://github.com/yesarpit.png","key":"arpit","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"the-hard-thing-about-hard-things-in-engineering","title":"What The Hard Thing About Hard Things Taught Me About Leading Through Pressure","authors":["arpit"],"tags":["leadership","engineering-management","books"],"description":"A leadership framework for engineering executives on counterintuitive decision-making and leading through high-stakes pressure."},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Decision Making Under Ambiguity","permalink":"/blog/decision-making-under-ambiguity"},"nextItem":{"title":"Team Topologies for Modern Financial and Platform Teams","permalink":"/blog/team-topologies-for-modern-platforms"}},"content":"### Read This\\n\\nSome leadership books are clean.\\n\\nThis one is not.\\n\\nThat is exactly why **The Hard Thing About Hard Things** works.\\n\\nIt does not pretend leadership is all clarity, confidence, and vision slides.\\n\\nIt talks about the messy part:\\n\\n* uncertainty\\n* pressure\\n* bad options\\n* layoffs\\n* underperformance\\n* morale damage\\n* trying to act calm when you are not calm\\n\\nThat is real leadership.\\nNot the LinkedIn version of it.\\n\\n\x3c!-- truncate --\x3e\\n\\n___\\n\\n### The biggest value of this book\\n\\nIt normalizes something important:\\n\\n**sometimes there is no clean answer**\\n\\nOnly hard trade-offs.\\n\\nAnd once you lead large teams or business-critical systems, you see this often.\\n\\nYou may have to choose between:\\n\\n* speed and rework risk\\n* loyalty and performance standards\\n* short-term calm and long-term truth\\n* keeping everyone comfortable and making necessary changes\\n\\nThat is the job.\\n\\nNot because leadership is glamorous.\\nBecause reality is messy.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### What stood out to me most\\n\\n#### 1) There are times when things are just hard\\n\\nThis sounds trivial.\\nBut it is actually powerful.\\n\\nMany leaders waste energy asking:\\n\\n\u201cwhy is this so difficult?\u201d\\n\\nBecause it is difficult.\\nThat is why leadership is being tested.\\n\\nSometimes the useful question is not \u201cwhy is this happening to me?\u201d\\n\\nIt is:\\n\\n\u201cwhat must I do clearly now?\u201d\\n\\n___\\n\\n#### 2) You cannot outsource hard conversations\\n\\nUnderperformance.\\nMisalignment.\\nBroken trust.\\nOrg drift.\\n\\nLeaders often delay these because they want one more week, one more signal, one more chance for things to self-correct.\\n\\nSometimes that patience is wise.\\nSometimes it is just avoidance wearing polite clothes.\\n\\nThis book is good at reminding you:\\n\\ndelayed truth usually becomes more expensive truth.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### 3) Peacetime leadership and wartime leadership are different\\n\\nI like this idea because it is practical.\\n\\nNot every season needs same leadership style.\\n\\nSometimes the right move is:\\n\\n* broad input\\n* exploration\\n* talent development\\n* patient decision making\\n\\nAnd sometimes the right move is:\\n\\n* tight priorities\\n* direct communication\\n* fast escalation paths\\n* zero ambiguity on ownership\\n\\nThe mistake is using one mode for every situation.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### 4) Culture is tested under pressure, not on posters\\n\\nEvery company says it values transparency.\\n\\nBut what happens when:\\n\\n* targets are missed?\\n* incidents pile up?\\n* key people leave?\\n* performance issue reaches senior level?\\n\\nThat is when culture becomes real.\\n\\nPressure reveals whether leadership values are actual operating principles or just decoration.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### What this means for engineering leaders\\n\\nIn engineering, especially in financial systems and platform teams, hard moments are unavoidable.\\n\\nYou will get:\\n\\n* production crises\\n* leadership mismatch\\n* org restructures\\n* delivery slippage\\n* strong people underperforming in bigger roles\\n\\nAnd many of these do not have elegant answers.\\n\\nSo the real question becomes:\\n\\nCan you stay clear without becoming cold?\\nCan you stay honest without becoming destructive?\\nCan you make hard decisions without becoming ego-driven?\\n\\nThat is serious leadership work.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### What I would apply\\n\\nPractical version:\\n\\n1. do not delay hard conversations unnecessarily\\n2. name the situation clearly before trying to fix it\\n3. adapt leadership mode to context\\n4. separate discomfort from wrongness\\n5. communicate more directly when stakes are high\\n\\nNone of this feels pleasant.\\nBut useful leadership is not always pleasant.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### Final thought\\n\\nWhat I like about this book is that it respects reality.\\n\\nIt does not sell leadership as neat wisdom.\\nIt presents it as judgment under pressure.\\n\\nAnd honestly, that feels much closer to what senior engineering leadership actually is.\\n\\nNot always having the answer.\\nBut being willing to face the hard thing without pretending it is easy."},{"id":"team-topologies-for-modern-platforms","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/team-topologies-for-modern-platforms","editUrl":"https://github.com/yesarpit/yesarpit.github.io/edit/main/blog/2024-08-18-team-topologies-for-modern-platforms.md","source":"@site/blog/2024-08-18-team-topologies-for-modern-platforms.md","title":"Team Topologies for Modern Financial and Platform Teams","description":"Exploring how org design and team boundaries influence software architecture in high-scale financial and platform engineering environments.","date":"2024-08-18T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"leadership","permalink":"/blog/tags/leadership"},{"inline":true,"label":"architecture","permalink":"/blog/tags/architecture"},{"inline":true,"label":"platform-engineering","permalink":"/blog/tags/platform-engineering"},{"inline":true,"label":"books","permalink":"/blog/tags/books"}],"readingTime":3.16,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Arpit Sharma","title":"Maintainer of this blog","url":"https://yesarpit.github.io","imageURL":"https://github.com/yesarpit.png","key":"arpit","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"team-topologies-for-modern-platforms","title":"Team Topologies for Modern Financial and Platform Teams","authors":["arpit"],"tags":["leadership","architecture","platform-engineering","books"],"description":"Exploring how org design and team boundaries influence software architecture in high-scale financial and platform engineering environments."},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"What The Hard Thing About Hard Things Taught Me About Leading Through Pressure","permalink":"/blog/the-hard-thing-about-hard-things-in-engineering"},"nextItem":{"title":"Why the Best Engineering Leaders Act Like Multipliers, Not Bottlenecks","permalink":"/blog/multipliers-for-engineering-leaders"}},"content":"### Read This\\n\\nA lot of engineering problems are not really architecture problems.\\n\\nThey look like architecture problems.\\nThey sound like architecture problems.\\nThey even get discussed in architecture meetings.\\n\\nBut many times the real issue is this:\\n\\n**team boundaries are wrong**\\n\\nThat is why **Team Topologies** is such a useful book.\\n\\nIt helps you see something many engineering leaders learn the hard way:\\n\\nbad org design creates bad software behavior.\\n\\n\x3c!-- truncate --\x3e\\n\\n___\\n\\n### Why this book matters\\n\\nWhen systems get bigger, complexity doesnt only live in code.\\nIt also lives in:\\n\\n* ownership confusion\\n* dependency chains\\n* platform bottlenecks\\n* too many handoffs\\n* teams carrying too much cognitive load\\n\\nAnd if you dont design around these, adding more people does not make system better.\\nIt just makes confusion scale faster.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### The idea I like most: cognitive load is real\\n\\nThis is the part many leaders ignore.\\n\\nA team can only hold so much in its head:\\n\\n* business rules\\n* infra knowledge\\n* deployment complexity\\n* security expectations\\n* stakeholder needs\\n* operational ownership\\n\\nAfter some point, the team is not lazy.\\nThe team is overloaded.\\n\\nAnd overloaded teams do predictable things:\\n\\n* avoid change\\n* copy old patterns\\n* make safe but mediocre decisions\\n* move slower than they should\\n\\nSo when a team looks \u201cslow\u201d, I always think this first:\\n\\nAre they weak?\\nOr are they carrying too much?\\n\\n___\\n\\n### The 4 team types are useful because they force clarity\\n\\nThe book talks about clear team patterns.\\n\\nI wont repeat whole framework here.\\nBut the practical value is this:\\n\\nnot every team should be doing everything.\\n\\nSome teams should own product flow.\\nSome should reduce platform friction.\\nSome should enable others temporarily.\\nSome should handle specialized expertise.\\n\\nThis sounds obvious.\\nBut many companies build teams like this instead:\\n\\n\u201cyou people do product, infra, reliability, compliance support, and data workflows also please\u201d\\n\\nThat is not empowerment.\\nThat is chaos with Jira access.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### Platform teams are often misunderstood\\n\\nA platform team is not valuable because it exists.\\n\\nIt is valuable only if it reduces friction for other teams.\\n\\nIf platform team creates:\\n\\n* tickets for everything\\n* slow approvals\\n* complicated onboarding\\n* too much internal documentation with little usability\\n\\nthen platform has become another dependency tax.\\n\\nGood platform teams feel like force multipliers.\\n\\nDevelopers should feel:\\n\\n\u201cnice, this made my work easier\u201d\\n\\nnot\\n\\n\u201cgreat, one more internal system to fight with\u201d\\n\\n___\\n\\n### Team interaction is where things get interesting\\n\\nThis is another strong point in the book.\\n\\nLeaders often focus only on team structure.\\nBut interaction model matters just as much.\\n\\nHow do teams work together?\\n\\n* are they collaborating too much for too long?\\n* are they blocked on a platform team?\\n* are they unclear on service ownership?\\n* are they depending on tribal knowledge?\\n\\nBecause if interaction mode is messy, structure alone wont save you.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### What this means in financial systems and enterprise platforms\\n\\nIn banks, fintechs, and enterprise engineering, this becomes even more important.\\n\\nBecause now you also have:\\n\\n* compliance\\n* security constraints\\n* change governance\\n* resilience expectations\\n* many cross-functional stakeholders\\n\\nSo if team boundaries are fuzzy, everything becomes slower.\\n\\nAnd then people say:\\n\\n\u201centerprise is slow\u201d\\n\\nSometimes yes.\\nBut sometimes org design is just poor.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### What I would apply\\n\\nPractical version:\\n\\n1. check if teams own clear outcomes, not vague components\\n2. reduce cognitive load before blaming execution\\n3. make platform teams usability-focused\\n4. review handoffs like you review architecture\\n5. redesign boundaries when dependency pain becomes chronic\\n\\nThis is not HR work.\\nThis is system design.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### Final thought\\n\\nSoftware architecture and org architecture keep leaking into each other.\\n\\nYou cannot fix one forever while ignoring the other.\\n\\nThat is why I like Team Topologies.\\n\\nIt reminds engineering leaders that scaling is not just about better code.\\n\\nSometimes it is about putting the right team around the right problem in the right way."},{"id":"multipliers-for-engineering-leaders","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/multipliers-for-engineering-leaders","editUrl":"https://github.com/yesarpit/yesarpit.github.io/edit/main/blog/2024-03-12-multipliers-for-engineering-leaders.md","source":"@site/blog/2024-03-12-multipliers-for-engineering-leaders.md","title":"Why the Best Engineering Leaders Act Like Multipliers, Not Bottlenecks","description":"Read This","date":"2024-03-12T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"leadership","permalink":"/blog/tags/leadership"},{"inline":true,"label":"engineering-management","permalink":"/blog/tags/engineering-management"},{"inline":true,"label":"books","permalink":"/blog/tags/books"}],"readingTime":2.74,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Arpit Sharma","title":"Maintainer of this blog","url":"https://yesarpit.github.io","imageURL":"https://github.com/yesarpit.png","key":"arpit","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"multipliers-for-engineering-leaders","title":"Why the Best Engineering Leaders Act Like Multipliers, Not Bottlenecks","authors":["arpit"],"tags":["leadership","engineering-management","books"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Team Topologies for Modern Financial and Platform Teams","permalink":"/blog/team-topologies-for-modern-platforms"},"nextItem":{"title":"A Note on Trust","permalink":"/blog/a-note-on-trust"}},"content":"### Read This\\n\\nSome leaders enter a room and make everyone sharper.\\n\\nSome leaders enter a room and make everyone quieter.\\n\\nThat is the simplest summary of **Multipliers**.\\n\\nThe book is basically asking:\\n\\nAre you making people think better?\\nOr are you making them wait for your answer?\\n\\nThis sounds simple.\\nBut in engineering leadership it is a huge difference.\\n\\n\x3c!-- truncate --\x3e\\n\\n___\\n\\n### The leadership trap\\n\\nA lot of capable leaders become accidental diminishers.\\n\\nNot because they are bad.\\nBecause they are smart, fast, experienced, and used to solving hard problems.\\n\\nSo what happens?\\n\\nThey:\\n\\n* answer too quickly\\n* jump into every hard decision\\n* rewrite other people\u2019s thinking\\n* over-direct experienced engineers\\n* treat meetings like approval gates\\n\\nFrom outside it looks like leadership.\\n\\nInside the team, it feels like this:\\n\\n\u201cwhy should I think deeply if final answer is already decided?\u201d\\n\\nThat is how strong teams become passive.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### Why this matters in engineering\\n\\nGood engineering orgs need local decision quality.\\n\\nThey cannot depend on one smart person for:\\n\\n* architecture direction\\n* delivery rescue\\n* incident decisions\\n* stakeholder translation\\n* talent growth\\n\\nThat model breaks at scale.\\n\\nAnd to be honest, it becomes exhausting too.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### What a multiplier does differently\\n\\n#### 1) Gives ownership, not just tasks\\n\\nTask is:\\n\u201cgo implement this\u201d\\n\\nOwnership is:\\n\u201cunderstand the problem, make trade-offs, and bring me the best path\u201d\\n\\nHuge difference.\\n\\nThe first creates executors.\\nThe second creates leaders.\\n\\n___\\n\\n#### 2) Uses questions well\\n\\nNot fake questions.\\nNot interrogation.\\n\\nReal questions like:\\n\\n* what problem are we actually solving?\\n* what assumption are we making?\\n* what fails if traffic doubles?\\n* where is the operational risk?\\n\\nGood questions dont slow the team.\\nThey improve thinking.\\n\\n___\\n\\n#### 3) Creates safe intellectual pressure\\n\\nI like this idea a lot.\\n\\nBest teams are not relaxed because nobody cares.\\nThey are sharp because standards are high and thinking is expected.\\n\\nSo multiplier leadership is not soft.\\n\\nIt means:\\n\\n* high bar\\n* strong ownership\\n* low ego\\n\\nThat combination is rare.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### What engineering leaders should watch out for\\n\\nThere are some signs that you may be becoming bottleneck:\\n\\n1. important decisions keep waiting for you\\n2. meetings become updates for your approval\\n3. senior people stop disagreeing openly\\n4. team quality drops when you step away\\n5. escalation volume stays high even after team growth\\n\\nThese are not random signals.\\nThey usually mean leverage is weak.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### My biggest takeaway\\n\\nAs leaders grow, temptation grows too.\\n\\nBecause you know more.\\nYou have seen failures.\\nYou can often predict the answer.\\n\\nBut if you always provide answer, you may be solving today\u2019s problem by weakening tomorrow\u2019s org.\\n\\nThis is where multiplier mindset becomes important.\\n\\nSometimes the job is not to be the smartest voice in the room.\\n\\nSometimes the job is to make the room smarter.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### What I would apply\\n\\nPractical version:\\n\\n* ask one more good question before giving answer\\n* delegate outcomes, not just tasks\\n* let senior engineers own trade-offs publicly\\n* reward clear thinking, not only fast execution\\n* check whether your presence improves energy or suppresses it\\n\\nThat last one is painful but useful.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### Final thought\\n\\nThe best engineering leaders are not only good problem solvers.\\n\\nThey are force multipliers for judgment, clarity, and confidence across the team.\\n\\nIf team can only be strong when leader is fully involved, leader is not scaling yet."},{"id":"a-note-on-trust","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/a-note-on-trust","editUrl":"https://github.com/yesarpit/yesarpit.github.io/edit/main/blog/2023-10-19-a-note-on-trust.md","source":"@site/blog/2023-10-19-a-note-on-trust.md","title":"A Note on Trust","description":"Read This","date":"2023-10-19T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"leadership","permalink":"/blog/tags/leadership"},{"inline":true,"label":"life-skills","permalink":"/blog/tags/life-skills"},{"inline":true,"label":"management","permalink":"/blog/tags/management"}],"readingTime":1.73,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Arpit Sharma","title":"Maintainer of this blog","url":"https://yesarpit.github.io","imageURL":"https://github.com/yesarpit.png","key":"arpit","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"a-note-on-trust","title":"A Note on Trust","authors":["arpit"],"tags":["leadership","life-skills","management"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Why the Best Engineering Leaders Act Like Multipliers, Not Bottlenecks","permalink":"/blog/multipliers-for-engineering-leaders"},"nextItem":{"title":"What Accelerate Means for Leaders Building High-Trust Engineering Teams","permalink":"/blog/accelerate-for-engineering-leaders"}},"content":"### Read This\\n\\nThis one is not a framework post.\\n\\nJust a note.\\n\\nThe longer I work with people and teams, the more I feel this:\\n\\n**trust is not a soft concept sitting outside execution**\\n\\nIt is part of execution.\\n\\nMaybe the most invisible part.\\n\\n\x3c!-- truncate --\x3e\\n\\n___\\n\\n### What trust changes\\n\\nWhen trust is high:\\n\\npeople speak earlier  \\nissues surface faster  \\ndisagreement becomes useful  \\nownership becomes lighter, not heavier  \\n\\nWhen trust is low:\\n\\npeople protect themselves  \\nupdates become political  \\nfeedback becomes late  \\nmeetings become performance  \\n\\nSame org chart.\\nVery different energy.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### Trust is built in small moments\\n\\nNot big speeches.\\n\\nSmall moments like:\\n\\n* do you react badly to bad news?\\n* do you keep your word on small things?\\n* do people feel safe disagreeing with you?\\n* do you give context or just authority?\\n* do you stay fair when stressed?\\n\\nThis is where trust grows.\\nOr quietly dies.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### One thing I keep noticing\\n\\nPeople say they want honesty.\\n\\nBut many environments punish honesty indirectly.\\n\\nThe person who raises risk gets labeled difficult.\\nThe person who asks hard question gets seen as negative.\\nThe person who surfaces problem early feels exposed.\\n\\nThen later everyone asks:\\n\\nwhy didnt anybody say this before?\\n\\nUsually because system trained them not to.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### Trust and speed are connected\\n\\nThis is why I dont see trust as separate from performance.\\n\\nHigh trust teams move faster because:\\n\\n* they escalate sooner\\n* they hide less\\n* they ask for help earlier\\n* they spend less energy managing perception\\n\\nThat is real speed.\\n\\nNot rushed motion.\\nCleaner motion.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### A small personal view\\n\\nI think trust is one of those things people notice more in absence than in presence.\\n\\nWhen it is there, work feels smoother.\\nWhen it is missing, everything becomes heavier than it should be.\\n\\nConversations become careful.\\nEnergy becomes fragmented.\\nEven good people start operating below their best.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### Final thought\\n\\nA lot of leadership advice talks about strategy, output, visibility, influence.\\n\\nAll useful.\\n\\nBut under many of those things, trust is quietly doing the real work.\\n\\nAnd if trust goes weak, everything else starts costing more."},{"id":"accelerate-for-engineering-leaders","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/accelerate-for-engineering-leaders","editUrl":"https://github.com/yesarpit/yesarpit.github.io/edit/main/blog/2023-09-21-accelerate-for-engineering-leaders.md","source":"@site/blog/2023-09-21-accelerate-for-engineering-leaders.md","title":"What Accelerate Means for Leaders Building High-Trust Engineering Teams","description":"Read This","date":"2023-09-21T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"leadership","permalink":"/blog/tags/leadership"},{"inline":true,"label":"engineering","permalink":"/blog/tags/engineering"},{"inline":true,"label":"books","permalink":"/blog/tags/books"},{"inline":true,"label":"devops","permalink":"/blog/tags/devops"}],"readingTime":2.78,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Arpit Sharma","title":"Maintainer of this blog","url":"https://yesarpit.github.io","imageURL":"https://github.com/yesarpit.png","key":"arpit","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"accelerate-for-engineering-leaders","title":"What Accelerate Means for Leaders Building High-Trust Engineering Teams","authors":["arpit"],"tags":["leadership","engineering","books","devops"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"A Note on Trust","permalink":"/blog/a-note-on-trust"},"nextItem":{"title":"What Good Leaders Repeat","permalink":"/blog/what-good-leaders-repeat"}},"content":"### Read This\\n\\nMany teams say:\\n\\nwe want speed  \\nwe want quality  \\nwe want stability  \\n\\nThen they behave as if they can pick only one.\\n\\nThat is exactly why **Accelerate** is useful.\\n\\nBecause it challenges one of the most common engineering myths:\\n\\n**speed and stability are not enemies by default**\\n\\nBad systems make them enemies.\\nGood systems improve both together.\\n\\n\x3c!-- truncate --\x3e\\n\\n___\\n\\n### What I like about this book\\n\\nIt is not based on \u201cmy experience says\u201d.\\n\\nIt is based on patterns observed across many teams.\\n\\nThat matters.\\n\\nBecause engineering leaders often fall in love with opinions:\\n\\n* \u201cmore process means control\u201d\\n* \u201cchange freezes improve reliability\u201d\\n* \u201clarge releases are safer because they are planned more\u201d\\n\\nAll of these can sound smart in meetings.\\nBut in practice, many times they create slow and fragile systems.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### 4 ideas that matter a lot\\n\\n#### 1) Deployment frequency matters\\n\\nIf releasing is painful, risky, political, and rare, your team is already paying tax.\\n\\nWhy?\\n\\nBecause rare releases create:\\n\\n* bigger batch sizes\\n* slower feedback\\n* more fear\\n* harder rollback\\n\\nSmaller, repeatable change is usually healthier.\\n\\nIn simple language:\\n\\nshipping more often is not chaos  \\nshipping unpredictably is chaos\\n\\n___\\n\\n#### 2) Lead time is a truth-teller\\n\\nHow long does it take for an idea or code change to reach production?\\n\\nThat number exposes many hidden problems:\\n\\n* unclear ownership\\n* weak review process\\n* slow test pipelines\\n* approval theatre\\n* architecture dependency mess\\n\\nWhen lead time is bad, culture is usually not the only issue.\\nSystem design and process design are also shouting.\\n\\n___\\n\\n#### 3) Reliability is not achieved by fear\\n\\nSome orgs try to achieve stability by making everyone scared of change.\\n\\nThat creates:\\n\\n* slow releases\\n* hidden risk\\n* delayed fixes\\n* blame-heavy culture\\n\\nReliable teams are not the teams that avoid change.\\nThey are teams that can make change safely.\\n\\nBig difference.\\n\\n___\\n\\n#### 4) Culture is not \u201csoft\u201d\\n\\nThis is where I strongly agree with the book.\\n\\nWhen teams have trust:\\n\\n* issues are raised earlier\\n* code reviews get better\\n* incidents become learning loops\\n* people dont waste energy on defensive politics\\n\\nSo yes, culture is a delivery topic.\\nNot HR wallpaper.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### What this means for engineering leaders\\n\\nIf you are leading a fintech, bank platform, or any serious engineering org, you cannot just ask:\\n\\n\u201cWhy is delivery slow?\u201d\\n\\nYou should ask:\\n\\n* how hard is it to release?\\n* how long does change take?\\n* how often do we recover from failure?\\n* what in our system creates fear?\\n\\nBecause output problems are often system problems.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### Things I would actually do\\n\\nAfter reading Accelerate, practical actions become clearer:\\n\\n1. reduce batch sizes\\n2. improve test confidence\\n3. shorten approval chains\\n4. make incidents learning-oriented\\n5. measure flow, not only effort\\n\\nAnd yes, dashboards help.\\nBut only if they lead to structural improvement.\\n\\nVanity metrics are still vanity metrics.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### One mistake leaders make\\n\\nThey hear \u201cmove fast\u201d and translate it into:\\n\\ndo more work  \\npush harder  \\nreduce discussion  \\n\\nThat is not what high performance means.\\n\\nHigh performance means reducing friction in the system so good work moves faster with less drama.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### Final thought\\n\\nFor me, Accelerate is really about this:\\n\\n**trust, engineering discipline, and delivery performance are deeply connected**\\n\\nIf a team has to choose between speed and stability all the time, that is usually not a people problem.\\n\\nThat is architecture, process, and leadership asking for attention."},{"id":"what-good-leaders-repeat","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/what-good-leaders-repeat","editUrl":"https://github.com/yesarpit/yesarpit.github.io/edit/main/blog/2023-03-08-what-good-leaders-repeat.md","source":"@site/blog/2023-03-08-what-good-leaders-repeat.md","title":"What Good Leaders Repeat","description":"Read This","date":"2023-03-08T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"leadership","permalink":"/blog/tags/leadership"},{"inline":true,"label":"management","permalink":"/blog/tags/management"},{"inline":true,"label":"communication","permalink":"/blog/tags/communication"}],"readingTime":2.27,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Arpit Sharma","title":"Maintainer of this blog","url":"https://yesarpit.github.io","imageURL":"https://github.com/yesarpit.png","key":"arpit","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"what-good-leaders-repeat","title":"What Good Leaders Repeat","authors":["arpit"],"tags":["leadership","management","communication"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"What Accelerate Means for Leaders Building High-Trust Engineering Teams","permalink":"/blog/accelerate-for-engineering-leaders"},"nextItem":{"title":"What High Output Management Still Gets Right for Engineering Leaders","permalink":"/blog/high-output-management-for-engineering-leaders"}},"content":"### Read This\\n\\nSome leaders love saying new things.\\n\\nGood for conferences.\\nNot always good for teams.\\n\\nBecause in actual teams, one of the most underrated leadership skills is not originality.\\n\\nIt is **useful repetition**.\\n\\nThe best leaders I have seen repeat the right things so consistently that people stop feeling confused even when work is hard.\\n\\n\x3c!-- truncate --\x3e\\n\\n___\\n\\n### Why repetition matters\\n\\nTeams forget.\\n\\nNot because they are careless.\\nBecause they are busy.\\n\\nPeople are dealing with:\\n\\n* sprint pressure\\n* roadmap changes\\n* production issues\\n* cross-team dependencies\\n* personal stress\\n\\nSo if a leader says something important once and assumes everyone \u201cgot it\u201d, that is usually fantasy.\\n\\nGood leadership often sounds repetitive from the speaker side and clarifying from the team side.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### What should be repeated?\\n\\nNot everything.\\n\\nOnly the few things that create stability.\\n\\nLike:\\n\\n* what matters most right now\\n* what good quality looks like\\n* what trade-offs we are willing to make\\n* how we make decisions\\n* what behaviors are non-negotiable\\n\\nThis kind of repetition builds operating rhythm.\\n\\nWithout it, teams start making up their own story.\\nAnd that is where misalignment quietly begins.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### Repetition is not lack of depth\\n\\nActually it is usually the opposite.\\n\\nIf something is truly important, it deserves repeated attention.\\n\\nVision needs repetition.\\nStandards need repetition.\\nValues under pressure definitely need repetition.\\n\\nPeople do not remember what leader said once in a perfect offsite slide.\\n\\nThey remember what leader kept reinforcing when reality got messy.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### The test is simple\\n\\nIf I ask 5 people in a team:\\n\\n* what matters most this quarter?\\n* how do we decide priorities?\\n* what does quality mean here?\\n\\nand I get 5 different answers,\\nthen leader has not communicated enough.\\n\\nOr not clearly enough.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### Repetition also creates trust\\n\\nWhen a leader keeps changing tone, priorities, and message every week, teams become cautious.\\n\\nNot because they are resistant.\\nBecause uncertainty increases.\\n\\nBut when leaders repeat the right things consistently, teams start feeling:\\n\\nokay, I know what this person stands for\\nI know what matters here\\nI know what will not randomly change tomorrow\\n\\nThat predictability is calming.\\nAnd calm teams think better.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### Things worth repeating in leadership\\n\\nIf I had to pick a few:\\n\\n1. what problem we are actually solving\\n2. where quality bar sits\\n3. how decisions get made\\n4. what kind of behavior is rewarded\\n5. what trade-offs we are not willing to make\\n\\nThis sounds basic.\\nIt is also where a lot of leadership strength lives.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### Final thought\\n\\nA lot of leaders try too hard to sound fresh.\\n\\nI think a better question is:\\n\\nwhat is so important that it deserves to be heard again?\\n\\nThat is often where the real leadership message is hiding."},{"id":"high-output-management-for-engineering-leaders","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/high-output-management-for-engineering-leaders","editUrl":"https://github.com/yesarpit/yesarpit.github.io/edit/main/blog/2023-02-14-high-output-management-for-engineering-leaders.md","source":"@site/blog/2023-02-14-high-output-management-for-engineering-leaders.md","title":"What High Output Management Still Gets Right for Engineering Leaders","description":"Analyzing Andy Grove\'s High Output Management through the lens of modern engineering leadership\u2014avoiding the bottleneck trap and scaling through leverage.","date":"2023-02-14T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"leadership","permalink":"/blog/tags/leadership"},{"inline":true,"label":"engineering-management","permalink":"/blog/tags/engineering-management"},{"inline":true,"label":"books","permalink":"/blog/tags/books"}],"readingTime":3,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Arpit Sharma","title":"Maintainer of this blog","url":"https://yesarpit.github.io","imageURL":"https://github.com/yesarpit.png","key":"arpit","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"high-output-management-for-engineering-leaders","title":"What High Output Management Still Gets Right for Engineering Leaders","authors":["arpit"],"tags":["leadership","engineering-management","books"],"description":"Analyzing Andy Grove\'s High Output Management through the lens of modern engineering leadership\u2014avoiding the bottleneck trap and scaling through leverage."},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"What Good Leaders Repeat","permalink":"/blog/what-good-leaders-repeat"},"nextItem":{"title":"Laws Of Human Nature","permalink":"/blog/2022/09/23/Laws-of-human-nature-Summary"}},"content":"### Read This\\n\\nMost people think leadership means:\\n\\nmore meetings  \\nmore escalations  \\nmore approvals  \\nmore visibility  \\n\\nNope.\\n\\nLeadership at scale is mostly about one thing:\\n\\n**Can your team produce good output without you becoming the bottleneck?**\\n\\nThat is why I still like **High Output Management**.\\n\\nIt is an old book, yes.\\nBut old doesnt mean outdated.\\n\\nSome books teach motivation.\\nThis one teaches operating system.\\n\\nAnd if you are leading engineering teams in fintech, banking, or any high pressure setup, operating system matters a lot more than motivational quotes.\\n\\n\x3c!-- truncate --\x3e\\n\\n___\\n\\n### What the book gets very right\\n\\n#### 1) Manager output is not just your output\\n\\nThis is the biggest thing.\\n\\nAs a manager, your output is:\\n\\n* what your team ships\\n* how your team makes decisions\\n* how fast your team learns\\n* whether your team can operate when you are not in the room\\n\\nThat sounds obvious.\\nBut many engineering leaders still behave like senior individual contributors with calendar access.\\n\\nThey solve the hardest issue themselves.\\nThey review every important PR.\\nThey attend every architecture meeting.\\nThey become the reliability layer for the entire org.\\n\\nIt works for some time.\\nThen the team slows down.\\n\\nWhy?\\n\\nBecause leader became middleware.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### 2) Meetings are not automatically waste\\n\\nPeople love saying:\\n> this meeting should have been an email\\n\\nSometimes true.\\nBut all meetings are not waste.\\n\\nA good meeting is a production system for clarity.\\n\\n1. 1:1s reduce hidden issues\\n2. staff meetings align teams\\n3. decision reviews prevent rework\\n4. planning meetings expose assumptions early\\n\\nBad meeting = status theatre  \\nGood meeting = decision acceleration\\n\\nIn high-scale engineering orgs, confusion is more expensive than meetings.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### 3) Task relevant maturity is real\\n\\nThis idea is underrated.\\n\\nSame person can be:\\n\\n* highly mature in system design\\n* medium mature in stakeholder handling\\n* low mature in org leadership\\n\\nSo managing everyone with one style is lazy.\\n\\nSome people need direction.\\nSome need context.\\nSome need challenge.\\nSome just need you to stop interfering.\\n\\nThat is real leadership.\\n\\nNot treating everyone same.\\nBut treating everyone fairly based on what helps them grow and deliver.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### 4) Leverage is the real game\\n\\nGood leaders create leverage through:\\n\\n* hiring well\\n* coaching well\\n* setting standards\\n* improving decision quality\\n* removing repeated friction\\n\\nExample:\\n\\nIf you solve one production issue yourself, good.\\n\\nIf you improve design review quality so 20 such issues dont happen, much better.\\n\\nIf you create stronger engineering managers who can do that without you, even better.\\n\\nThis is how senior leadership starts looking different from just \u201cworking hard\u201d.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### What I take from it as an engineering leader\\n\\nFor me this book is not about \u201chow to manage\u201d.\\n\\nIt is about how to avoid becoming accidental bottleneck while thinking you are helping.\\n\\nEspecially in financial systems, payments, platform teams, or enterprise engineering:\\n\\n* complexity is high\\n* dependencies are real\\n* stakes are high\\n* speed still matters\\n\\nSo leadership cannot just be inspiration.\\nIt has to be operational.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### What I would actually apply\\n\\nIf I reduce the whole book into practical points:\\n\\n1. define output clearly\\n2. create repeatable operating rhythm\\n3. invest in 1:1s seriously\\n4. calibrate people based on task maturity, not title\\n5. measure whether team quality improves without your constant intervention\\n\\nIf that last one is not happening, something is wrong.\\n\\n___\\n\\n### Final thought\\n\\nHigh Output Management is still relevant because engineering leadership is still same in one important way:\\n\\nthe higher you go, the less your value comes from doing the work yourself.\\n\\nYour real value comes from building a system where good work keeps happening.\\n\\nThat is hard.\\nThat is also the job."},{"id":"/2022/09/23/Laws-of-human-nature-Summary","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/2022/09/23/Laws-of-human-nature-Summary","editUrl":"https://github.com/yesarpit/yesarpit.github.io/edit/main/blog/2022-09-23-Laws-of-human-nature-Summary.md","source":"@site/blog/2022-09-23-Laws-of-human-nature-Summary.md","title":"Laws Of Human Nature","description":"1. LAW OF IRRATIONALITY: Master Your Emotional Self","date":"2022-09-23T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[],"readingTime":7.06,"hasTruncateMarker":false,"authors":[],"frontMatter":{"created":"2022-08-23T15:48:27.000Z","modified":"2022-08-23T16:17:25.000Z"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"What High Output Management Still Gets Right for Engineering Leaders","permalink":"/blog/high-output-management-for-engineering-leaders"},"nextItem":{"title":"Chakras","permalink":"/blog/2022/07/28/Our-Chakras"}},"content":"1. LAW OF IRRATIONALITY: Master Your Emotional Self\\n\\n    Humans think that we\u2019re rational and in control of our lives, when in reality we\u2019re driven by irrational emotions. We\u2019re often guided by our emotional impulses\u2014we seek pleasure, avoid pain and do things to soothe our ego.\\n\\n    Emotions and conscious thought are located in different parts of the brain\u2014we first feel an emotion before we interpret it consciously (and often wrongly). It\u2019s easier to think that you\u2019re angry with someone because he\u2019s a jerk, than to admit that you\u2019re insecure and jealous of him. In short, we\u2019re emotional creatures, yet we\u2019re often blind to our own impulses. Become aware of your own irrationality, then train yourself to learn and manage them through introspection and reflection.\\n\\n    Digest these powerful ideas in minutes with our full summary & infographic!\\n\\n    *BECOMING MORE RATIONAL*\\n    To become more rational, incorporate these 3 steps into your life:\\n\\n\u2022 Recognize biases (or \u201clow-grade irrationality\u201d) that distort your perception and responses. These include the (i) confirmation bias (thinking you\u2019re being logical when you\u2019re focusing on evidence to confirm your own beliefs), (ii) conviction bias (defending your views with conviction to drown out your doubts), (iii) appearance bias (thinking you can read people when you\u2019re misled by them), (iv) group bias (thinking your ideas are original when you\u2019re following the herd), (v) superiority bias (thinking you\u2019re better and more rational than others) and (vi) blame bias (avoiding your own failures and blaming others).\\n\\n\u2022 Beware of inflaming factors (or \u201chigh-grade irrationality\u201d) which call up certain feelings and intensify them. These may come from (i) childhood memories that trigger strong positive/negative feelings, (ii) sudden gains/losses that bring extreme optimism or pessimism, (iii) extreme stress which causes us to get defensive, (iv) individuals who evoke strong feelings in us/others, and (v) infectious emotions from large groups. Watch out for these factors, detach yourself and contemplate the underlying sources.\\n\\n\u2022 Develop your rational self: (i) observe yourself in times of stress, (ii) examine the roots of your feelings and record your observations, (iii) wait before you respond, (iv) accept irrational people as facts of life (vs taking things personally), and (iv) consciously channel your emotional energy instead of being driven by them.\\n\\n2. LAW OF NARCISSISM: Transform Self-Love into Empathy\\nHumans possess the natural ability to empathize and connect with others. Unfortunately, we get blinded by self-absorption. Our sense of self-worth is tied to the attention we receive and the quality of our interactions. The problem arises when we rely on others\u2019 attention and validation to feel worthy and alive.\\n\\nWe are all narcissists to varying degrees. Deep narcissists lack a cohesive sense of self, so their self-worth comes entirely from others\u2019 attention and validation. They tend to take everything personally, demand control and attention in their relationships and are expert manipulators as leaders. Most of us are functional narcissists in the middle of the spectrum. We may slip into moments of self-absorption, but have a strong-enough sense of self to pull out of it. Healthy narcissists have a strong, resilient sense of self. They direct their sensitivity outward\u2014in the form of empathy toward people or focused creativity in their work\u2014instead of inward.\\n\\nSHIFT TOWARD HEALTHY NARCISSISM\\nAim to (i) recognize deep narcissism to avoid being sucked into toxic relationships, (ii) be honest about your true nature, and (iii) shift toward healthy narcissism by developing 4 empathic skills:\\n\\n\u2022 Empathetic attitude: Assume you\u2019re ignorant about people and be truly curious about their point of view. In your daily conversations, (i) set aside your judgments/biases, (ii) stop your inner dialogue and listen fully, (iii) don\u2019t assume you have similar/shared views, and (iv) be open to new discoveries.\\n\\n\u2022 Visceral empathy: Pay attention to people\u2019s reactions, e.g. facial expressions, body language and tone of voice. Use mirroring to develop a stronger connection, e.g. mimic their tone or expression, nod and smile as you listen.\\n\\n\u2022 Analytic empathy: gather info about the other person to know them (e.g. family relationships, values, emotional triggers).\\n\\n\u2022 Use direct/indirect feedback to develop your empathetic skills: ask about their thoughts/feelings to verify your guesses, and observe their responses and rapport.\\n\\n   \\n3. Law of Role Playing: See though people\u2019s masks.  Become a master at reading people and presenting yourself optimally with 3 skills.\\n\\n4. Law of Compulsive Behavior: Know people\u2019s character. When choosing who to work/associate with, learn to look beyond appearances. Learn to assess your own character (so you can address the negative patterns in your life) and becoming skilled at reading others\u2019 character.\\n\\n5. Law of Covetousness: Become an elusive object of desire. It\u2019s human tendency to covet what we don\u2019t have. Learn and apply the 3 strategies for stimulating desire.\\n\\n6. Law of Shortsightedness: Elevate your perspective. Learn to step back and consider the bigger picture instead of reacting to what\u2019s in front of you. Recognize and overcome the 4 signs of shortsightedness.\\n\\n7. Law of Defensiveness: Confirm people\u2019s self-opinion. To influence someone, don\u2019t try to show how good you are nor challenge them directly. Instead, use 5 strategies to soften their defenses (by validating their self-opinion and aligning your idea with it).\\n\\n8. Law of Self-sabotage: Your attitude shapes your situation. Our attitude affects how we interpret and respond to events/people, thus creating a self-fulfilling effect. Overcome 5 constricted attitudes and embrace expansive ones, to improve your circumstances.\\n\\n9. Law of Repression: Confront your dark side. We all have a dark side (e.g. the selfish, greedy, or aggressive parts of ourselves) that we hide in order to fit in and be liked/respected. Recognize the 7 common emphatic traits that hide a darker side, and use 4 steps to tap on your full range of creative energies and become an integrated human.\\n\\n10. Law of Envy: Beware the fragile ego. Humans constantly compare ourselves with one another, and deny our own envy/jealousy. Learn to decode and diffuse envy before it turns dangerous. Learn the signs of envy, the 5 envier types, the situations that often trigger active envy, and how to build your self-worth.\\n\\n11. Law of Grandiosity: Know your limits. Humans want to think highly of ourselves, to the point we tend to imagine our superiority. Learn to identify the signs of elevated grandiosity in yourself and in others, including the 6 common illusions of grandiose leaders and how you can adopt practical grandiosity.\\n\\n12. Law of Gender Rigidity: Reconnect to your masculinity/femininity. Every human has both masculine and feminine qualities genes, and hormones. Learn to recognize 6 types of gender projections and unlock your repressed qualities/energy to become more flexible, balanced and effective.\\n\\n13. Law of Aimlessness: Advance with a sense of purpose. Use 5 strategies to overcome in-the-moment impulses to develop a sense of purpose and follow your inner compass.\\n\\n14. Law of Conformity: Resist the groups\u2019 downward pull. We like to believe that we\u2019re independent and progressive, but we can\u2019t help conforming with our groups. Develop group intelligence by knowing how you\u2019re individually influenced by groups and recognize the dynamics/patterns found in any group, then use 5 strategies to develop healthy groups with an upward pull.\\n\\n15. Law of Fickleness: Make them want to follow you. We want to believe that our emotions are pure and simple, when we\u2019re actually ambivalent toward most things, including our leaders. Learn to establish your authority with 8 strategies and cultivate your inner authority.\\n\\n16. Law of Aggression: See the hostility behind the fa\xe7ade. On the surface, people seem friendly and civilized. But beneath the mask, everyone has an aggressive side. Learn to recognize and manage chronic aggressors, counter passive-aggression, be aware of your own aggressive tendencies, and harness 4 positive aspects of your assertive energy.\\n\\n17. Law of Generational Myopia: Seize the historical moment. We\u2019re strongly defined by the generation that we\u2019re born into. Realize how history moves in cycles across 4 generations, understand how your generation\u2019s spirit affects you, and how/where you fit in the wider generational patterns. Then, use several strategies to exploit the spirit of the times.\\n\\n18. Law of Death Denial: Contemplate common mortality. Instead of avoiding thoughts of death, leverage the paradoxical death effect\u2013use the awareness of your mortality to make your life more productive and meaningful.\\n\\n\\nSO these were the 18 laws. Entire content has been copied from internet, as it has been written beautifully @readingraphics."},{"id":"/2022/07/28/Our-Chakras","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/2022/07/28/Our-Chakras","editUrl":"https://github.com/yesarpit/yesarpit.github.io/edit/main/blog/2022-07-28-Our-Chakras.md","source":"@site/blog/2022-07-28-Our-Chakras.md","title":"Chakras","description":"1) Root chakra ( Muladhar Chakra)","date":"2022-07-28T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[],"readingTime":1.72,"hasTruncateMarker":false,"authors":[],"frontMatter":{"created":"2022-11-30T15:12:02.000Z","modified":"2022-11-30T15:12:13.000Z"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Laws Of Human Nature","permalink":"/blog/2022/09/23/Laws-of-human-nature-Summary"},"nextItem":{"title":"The Backwards Law: Why Trying Harder Doesn\'t Always Work","permalink":"/blog/2022/04/16/the-backwater-law"}},"content":"# Know your chakras - ( session from Intellectual Indies youtube)\\n\\n## 1) Root chakra ( Muladhar Chakra)\\n\\n#### Base of spine , red energy emmision \\n- sceintific explanation - it is adrenaline gland\\n- people who are low on energy and who doesnt feel like doing anything or getting up in the morning have less adrenaline hormones\\n- excercise helps to keep it active\\n- emits engery and attracts people\\n- make your frnd circle full of engery to enhance this chakra\\n\\n\\n\\n## 2) Sakral chakra ( Swadishtan Chakra)\\n\\n#### Above root chakra , orange in color\\n- it controls emotions when to get angry, happy etc\\n- sceintific explanation - endocrine glands\\n- it\'s like magnetism , if people get attracted to you then this is your active chakra\\nIf this chakra is:\\n- open - joyful, Adventurous\\n- close - alone, limited frnd circle, fixed routine, think negative of themselves\\n way to open this: \\n- make happiness a priority\\n\\n## 3) Solar Plexus chakra ( Manipur Chakra) \\n\\n#### Around navel in abdomen, yellow color\\n- will power, successful\\n- we need to increase will power to enhance this chakra\\n- keep small tasks and complete them to increase will power\\n\\n## 4) Heart Chakra ( Hridaya Chakra)\\n\\n#### Center of chest, green color\\n- thymus gland\\n- close body indicates that this chakra is closed\\n- when it\'s powerful - you see everyone with love\\n- forgive everyone to enhance this chakra\\n- close - cold hand , like lonliness\\n- meditation is helpful for this\\n- gratitude practice, write 3 reasons why you are happy \\n- when you gratitude, you attract success\\n\\n## 5) Throat Chakra ( Vishuddhi Chakra)\\n\\n#### Throat, blue color, thyroid gland, element- ether\\n- excessive speaking - extra open\\n- share knowledge - helps to strengthen chkra\\n- write journal - say truth, write truth to enhance this\\n- low volume - means this chakra is close\\n\\n\\n## 6) Third eye chakra ( Agya Chakra)\\n\\n#### Forehead, Pituatiory gland, pineal gland, Ivory color\\n- knowledge chakra\\n- education seeker, intuition\\n- observing people, deep thinker\\n\\n\\n## 7) Crown Chakra ( Sahastrasaar Chakra)\\n\\n#### Top of head, violet royal blue color\\n- Old kings used to wear violet color gowns as they knew it\\n- Penial Gland ( antenna )  center of brain\\n - englightment\\n - regulate bmt harmone \\n - beleive in universe\\n - down - if you feel nothing is working for you\\n - try to read universal interpretations to enhance it"},{"id":"/2022/04/16/the-backwater-law","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/2022/04/16/the-backwater-law","editUrl":"https://github.com/yesarpit/yesarpit.github.io/edit/main/blog/2022-04-16-the-backwater-law.md","source":"@site/blog/2022-04-16-the-backwater-law.md","title":"The Backwards Law: Why Trying Harder Doesn\'t Always Work","description":"The Backwards Law: The Art of Letting Go","date":"2022-04-16T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"shorts","permalink":"/blog/tags/shorts"},{"inline":true,"label":"philosophy","permalink":"/blog/tags/philosophy"},{"inline":true,"label":"mindset","permalink":"/blog/tags/mindset"}],"readingTime":0.95,"hasTruncateMarker":false,"authors":[{"name":"Alan Watts","title":"Original Philosopher","key":"alanwatts","page":null},{"name":"Arpit Sharma","title":"Maintainer of this blog","url":"https://yesarpit.github.io","imageURL":"https://github.com/yesarpit.png","key":"arpit","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"title":"The Backwards Law: Why Trying Harder Doesn\'t Always Work","authors":["alanwatts","arpit"],"tags":["shorts","philosophy","mindset"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Chakras","permalink":"/blog/2022/07/28/Our-Chakras"},"nextItem":{"title":"Rich Dad\'s Guide to Investing: Building Lasting Wealth","permalink":"/blog/2022/04/15/rich-dad-guide-to-investing"}},"content":"## The Backwards Law: The Art of Letting Go\\n\\nThe \\"Backwards Law,\\" a term famously explored by philosopher Alan Watts, posits a counter-intuitive truth: **The harder you try to get a result, the further away it moves.**\\n\\n### The Paradox of Desire\\nAlan Watts was a British writer who translated Eastern philosophy for the Western world. He famously wrote:\\n> \\"Wanting a positive experience is a negative experience; accepting a negative experience is a positive experience.\\"\\n\\nThis is the core of the Backwards Law. When you pursue happiness, you are reinforcing the fact that you *lack* it in the first place. This constant chase makes you less satisfied.\\n\\n### Real-Life Examples:\\n1.  **Sleep**: The more you worry about falling asleep, the more awake you stay.\\n2.  **Social Ease**: The harder you try to \\"look cool\\" or \\"act natural,\\" the more awkward you become.\\n3.  **Confidence**: The truly confident person doesn\'t need to feel confident; they are simply okay with whatever happens.\\n\\n**Conclusion**: Sometimes, stepping back and accepting the current situation\u2014even if it\'s negative\u2014is the fastest way to improve it. In many situations, struggling only makes the water murkier.\\n\\n#learnings"},{"id":"/2022/04/15/rich-dad-guide-to-investing","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/2022/04/15/rich-dad-guide-to-investing","editUrl":"https://github.com/yesarpit/yesarpit.github.io/edit/main/blog/2022-04-15-rich-dad-guide-to-investing.md","source":"@site/blog/2022-04-15-rich-dad-guide-to-investing.md","title":"Rich Dad\'s Guide to Investing: Building Lasting Wealth","description":"Key Principles from Rich Dad\'s Guide to Investing","date":"2022-04-15T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"book-summary","permalink":"/blog/tags/book-summary"},{"inline":true,"label":"finance","permalink":"/blog/tags/finance"},{"inline":true,"label":"investing","permalink":"/blog/tags/investing"}],"readingTime":1.2,"hasTruncateMarker":false,"authors":[{"name":"Robert Kiyosaki","title":"Original Author","key":"kiyosaki","page":null},{"name":"Arpit Sharma","title":"Maintainer of this blog","url":"https://yesarpit.github.io","imageURL":"https://github.com/yesarpit.png","key":"arpit","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Rich Dad\'s Guide to Investing: Building Lasting Wealth","authors":["kiyosaki","arpit"],"tags":["book-summary","finance","investing"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"The Backwards Law: Why Trying Harder Doesn\'t Always Work","permalink":"/blog/2022/04/16/the-backwater-law"},"nextItem":{"title":"Own It: What Maturity Actually Means","permalink":"/blog/2022/04/09/own-it-like-matured"}},"content":"## Key Principles from Rich Dad\'s Guide to Investing\\n\\nRobert Kiyosaki\u2019s guide isn\'t about particular stocks; it\'s about the **Mindset** of an investor. Here is the distilled wisdom on building an investment-first lifestyle:\\n\\n### 1. Distinguish Good vs. Bad \\"Investments\\"\\nKiyosaki warns against using your capital for \\"liabilities\\" disguised as lifestyle upgrades.\\n*   **Bad Moves**: Quitting a steady job for a \\"world tour\\" without passive income, or liquidating family stability for shallow desires.\\n*   **Asset-First**: Every profit should be reinvested. The goal is to maximize the gap between your income and your living expenses by using that gap to buy more assets.\\n\\n### 2. The 3 E\'s of an Investor\\nTo be a successful investor, you must acquire these three \\"E\'s\\":\\n1.  **Education**: Financial literacy is your #1 asset. Investment without knowledge is just gambling.\\n2.  **Experience**: Start small. You need the \\"street smarts\\" of seeing how numbers move in real-time.\\n3.  **Excess Cash**: Never let cash sit idle. Use it to acquire more \\"meaningful work\\" (like hiring employees for monotonous tasks) so your own time is freed up for high-level strategy.\\n\\n### 3. Investment as a Knowledge Compound\\nKnowledge is a unique asset because it compounds faster than money. By investing in yourself\u2014through books, seminars, and networking\u2014you become an \\"Inside Investor.\\" \\n\\n**The Golden Rule**: Never buy a stock just to sell it. Buy the company because you believe in its value as if it were your own business.\\n\\n#learnings"},{"id":"/2022/04/09/own-it-like-matured","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/2022/04/09/own-it-like-matured","editUrl":"https://github.com/yesarpit/yesarpit.github.io/edit/main/blog/2022-04-09-own-it-like-matured.md","source":"@site/blog/2022-04-09-own-it-like-matured.md","title":"Own It: What Maturity Actually Means","description":"What Does it Really Mean to be Mature?","date":"2022-04-09T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"book-summary","permalink":"/blog/tags/book-summary"},{"inline":true,"label":"personal-growth","permalink":"/blog/tags/personal-growth"},{"inline":true,"label":"mindset","permalink":"/blog/tags/mindset"}],"readingTime":1.4,"hasTruncateMarker":false,"authors":[{"name":"Arpit Sharma","title":"Maintainer of this blog","url":"https://yesarpit.github.io","imageURL":"https://github.com/yesarpit.png","key":"arpit","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Own It: What Maturity Actually Means","authors":"arpit","tags":["book-summary","personal-growth","mindset"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Rich Dad\'s Guide to Investing: Building Lasting Wealth","permalink":"/blog/2022/04/15/rich-dad-guide-to-investing"},"nextItem":{"title":"Primal Learning - How Brain learns","permalink":"/blog/primal-learning"}},"content":"## What Does it Really Mean to be Mature?\\n\\nMost people define maturity by age, but real maturity is binary: **It is the ability to own your actions (and even others\' mistakes) to find a solution rather than a target for blame.**\\n\\n### The Lesson of the Croma Cooler\\nI recently had a frustrating experience with an online order. I needed a replacement for a faulty air cooler. When the pickup agent was rude and refused to take the unboxed unit, I reacted predictably: I matched his tone, defended my stance, and slammed the door.\\n\\n**Result**: A week passed, and I was still stuck with a broken cooler and a heated mood.\\n\\nIf I had shown **maturity**\u2014owning the outcome (getting the cooler replaced) instead of the ego-clash\u2014I could have handled it differently, stayed calm, and resolved the issue that same day.\\n\\n### 10 Pillars of Maturity\\nTo be mature is to master these habits:\\n1.  **Take Responsibility**: Don\'t just own your successes; own your blockers.\\n2.  **No Complaints**: Focus on \\"What\'s next?\\" instead of \\"Why me?\\"\\n3.  **Stop Gossiping**: Small minds discuss people; mature minds discuss ideas.\\n4.  **Self-Awareness**: List your own weaknesses. Knowing them is the first step to neutralizing them.\\n5.  **Leave Ego Behind**: Ego is a barrier to learning.\\n6.  **Seek Value, Not Attention**: Do great work, and the praise will find you.\\n7.  **Total Honesty**: Small lies build a weak foundation.\\n8.  **The Emotional/Rational Balance**: Feel your emotions, but let your rational mind lead.\\n9.  **Calm Response to Rejection**: Rejection is just data, not a personal attack.\\n10. **Stay Curious**: Maturity isn\'t \\"knowing everything.\\" Keep the child within alive by asking questions.\\n\\n#learnings"},{"id":"primal-learning","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/primal-learning","editUrl":"https://github.com/yesarpit/yesarpit.github.io/edit/main/blog/2021-11-16-primal-learning-summary.md","source":"@site/blog/2021-11-16-primal-learning-summary.md","title":"Primal Learning - How Brain learns","description":"Mylan coating around brain cells help you retrieve faster","date":"2021-11-16T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"summary","permalink":"/blog/tags/summary"}],"readingTime":2.94,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Arpit Sharma","title":"Maintainer of this blog","url":"https://yesarpit.github.io","imageURL":"https://github.com/yesarpit.png","key":"arpit","page":null},{"name":"Vegard Gjerde","title":"Ph.D. Physics Education Research","url":"https://www.udemy.com/user/vegardgjerde/","imageURL":"https://img-b.udemycdn.com/user/200_H/11805206_c4a1.jpg","key":"vegardgjerde","page":null},{"name":"Mathias G","title":"Software entrepreneur & engineer","url":"https://www.udemy.com/user/54a6106b68452/","imageURL":"https://img-b.udemycdn.com/user/200_H/9914004_1268_4.jpg","key":"mathiasg","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"primal-learning","title":"Primal Learning - How Brain learns","authors":["arpit","vegardgjerde","mathiasg"],"tags":["summary"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Own It: What Maturity Actually Means","permalink":"/blog/2022/04/09/own-it-like-matured"},"nextItem":{"title":"Ego is the Enemy: Staying Humble in Every Stage","permalink":"/blog/2021/01/05/ego-is-the-enemy-book-summary"}},"content":"Mylan coating around brain cells help you retrieve faster\\n\\n## Use it or lose it\\n\\n\x3c!--truncate--\x3e\\nImplicit:\\n\\nYou learn more per hour if you space it out\\n\\nYou become average of the 5 people you spend most time with\\n\\nExplicit:\\n\\nExercise and Meditation helps\\n\\n\\nDo important things first\\n\\nKeep a distraction log- remember what distract you - becoming aware of what distracts you\\n\\n\\nReference memory:\\n\\n\\nGreen tea black tea and breath- alpha memory ( concentration )\\n\\nTheta memory - 2 to 5years child - extraordinary learning\\n\\nSet goal regular for dopamine release which will help you learn\\n\\n\\nGoals: subgoals\\nDeadlines: many nd short\\n\\nEach deadline you miss if you \\n\\nCold showers it Increase dopamine level by 250% and 500% noradrenaline\\n\\nVary exercise and push your limits for great endorphins release\\n\\n\\nStart singletasking\\n\\nA day without setting goal is a day when you are not operating your best\\n\\n\\n1) struggle phase\\n\\nFind out what you are afraid of and create strong emotional attachment\\n\\n1) start easy\\n2) reward yourself for small goals\\n3) start moving, get up and walk around , moving around motion create emotion\\n4) create deadline\\n5) get accountability partner\\n6) get mad at fear\\nCortisol + noradrenaline they create uneasy feeling at start\\n\\nThe more something threatens your identity more you will avoid doing it\\n\\n2) release phase\\n     \\n3) flow\\n\\nDo what you love\\nFlow healthy life\\n\\n4) Recovery\\n\\n\\nEmbrace struggle\\n\\n\\n+Optimal learning strategy\\n\\n>>80/20\\n20 percentage of action leads to 80percent result\\n\\n>>Parkinson\'s law\\nWorks expands to fill the time given\\n \\nSet Tight deadlines are necessary to get best out of you\\n\\n>> Blooms taxonomy\\nSchool learning system is failing\\n\\nCreating - is the most efficient way to learn something followed by \\nEvaluating, \\nAnalyzing,\\nApplying,\\nUnderstanding\\nRemember (passive Learning, bad approach)\\n\\n>>Behavioursm\\nSurrounding yourself with talented and knowledgeable person\\n\\n>>Conitivismks\\nFind connection between what you know and new learning helps strengthen neuro transmitters\\nDevelop your mindset, common people think they can\'t be good at maths, but its not correct\\nKeep reading and learning makes you strong\\n\\n>>Constructivism\\nPassive reading and listening to video is not efficient way of learning, create something out of your learning : most impotant - start with complex problem and on the way to resolve that learn basics\\n\\n+Optimal Learning Techniques\\n>>Retrieval Practice\\n>> Distributed practice\\nReasearch has shown that when learning is distributed uniformly across week brings more learning.\\nYou need to space out your practice session across days intead of all at once in one day\\n>>Practice test\\nReasearch shows taking practice test aftrer chapters is more effective than revising\\nAlso you can find a study partner and ask questions to each other.\\n\\n>> Inter leaved practice\\nMixing several types of items while practicing . Block practicing - example in badminton if you try different types of serve instead of just doing one service at time brings better results in long term\\n>>Elaborative intervention\\nAsk why intead of what\\nThe more learning hooks you create more space will form for new learning\\n\\n>>Self explanattion\\nExplain to yourself with efforts. So that brai. Can remember it.explain to urself as if prac\\n\\n>> Lifetayle\\nImprove sleep quality\\n\\n>> Excerise\\nBalances neurotransmitter\\nIncrease brain volume\\nSmoking= sitting\\nWalking+ audiobooks great combination\\n\\n>>Fasting\\nProduces energy\\nImprove memory\\nIt takes a while for body to adapylt\\n5:2 fasting - eat 300k cals on 2 days of fasting, \\n\\n>>Meditation\\nIt physically change brain structure\\nIt Increase grey matter\\nIncreAses volume of cerebral\\n8 weeks of daily meditation enhance brain size\\nStress in induced by own though- Meditation helps\\nPlacebo effect.\\nAttention and working memory increased in 12 weeks of meditation\\n\\n#learnings"},{"id":"/2021/01/05/ego-is-the-enemy-book-summary","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/2021/01/05/ego-is-the-enemy-book-summary","editUrl":"https://github.com/yesarpit/yesarpit.github.io/edit/main/blog/2021-01-05-ego-is-the-enemy-book-summary.md","source":"@site/blog/2021-01-05-ego-is-the-enemy-book-summary.md","title":"Ego is the Enemy: Staying Humble in Every Stage","description":"Ego is the Enemy - The Three Stages of Life","date":"2021-01-05T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"book-summary","permalink":"/blog/tags/book-summary"},{"inline":true,"label":"mindset","permalink":"/blog/tags/mindset"},{"inline":true,"label":"philosophy","permalink":"/blog/tags/philosophy"}],"readingTime":1.26,"hasTruncateMarker":false,"authors":[{"name":"Arpit Sharma","title":"Maintainer of this blog","url":"https://yesarpit.github.io","imageURL":"https://github.com/yesarpit.png","key":"arpit","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Ego is the Enemy: Staying Humble in Every Stage","authors":"arpit","tags":["book-summary","mindset","philosophy"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Primal Learning - How Brain learns","permalink":"/blog/primal-learning"},"nextItem":{"title":"Drop the Labels: How to Connect with Anyone","permalink":"/blog/2020/12/30/drop-label-before-you-talk"}},"content":"## Ego is the Enemy - The Three Stages of Life\\n\\nRyan Holiday argues that at any given time, we are in one of three stages: **Aspire, Success, or Failure**. In each stage, ego is the enemy that prevents us from moving forward.\\n\\n### 1. Aspire\\nWhen you are starting (e.g., preparing for an exam or launching a project), ego wants you to *talk* more than you *work*. \\n*   **Silence is Rare**: Speaking about your goals releases a premature sense of accomplishment. Waste your energy on the action, not the announcement.\\n*   **Document Your Work**: Henry Ford once said, \\"You can\'t build a reputation based on what you *are going* to do.\\"\\n\\n### 2. Success\\nSuccess is often where the real danger begins. It makes us believe we are \\"special\\" or \\"above\\" the rules.\\n*   **Keep Your Identity Small**: The more you identify with your fame, title, or property, the more you have to lose.\\n*   **Stay a Student**: The moment you think you \\"know it all,\\" you stop growing. If you can\'t swallow your pride, you can\'t lead.\\n\\n### 3. Failure\\nFailure is inevitable, but how you react to it defines you.\\n*   **Alive Time vs. Dead Time**: \\"Dead time\\" is when you are passive and waiting for things to change. \\"Alive time\\" is when you are utilizing every second of the failure to learn and prepare for the next round.\\n*   **Sweeping the Floor**: Legend has it that the floor needs to be swept every single day. Similarly, your talent and mindset need daily practice, or they will gather dust.\\n\\n#learnings"},{"id":"/2020/12/30/drop-label-before-you-talk","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/2020/12/30/drop-label-before-you-talk","editUrl":"https://github.com/yesarpit/yesarpit.github.io/edit/main/blog/2020-12-30-drop-label-before-you-talk.md","source":"@site/blog/2020-12-30-drop-label-before-you-talk.md","title":"Drop the Labels: How to Connect with Anyone","description":"Connection Over Classification","date":"2020-12-30T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"communication","permalink":"/blog/tags/communication"},{"inline":true,"label":"mindset","permalink":"/blog/tags/mindset"}],"readingTime":1.15,"hasTruncateMarker":false,"authors":[{"name":"Arpit Sharma","title":"Maintainer of this blog","url":"https://yesarpit.github.io","imageURL":"https://github.com/yesarpit.png","key":"arpit","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Drop the Labels: How to Connect with Anyone","authors":"arpit","tags":["communication","mindset"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Ego is the Enemy: Staying Humble in Every Stage","permalink":"/blog/2021/01/05/ego-is-the-enemy-book-summary"},"nextItem":{"title":"Atomic Habits: How Small Changes Lead to Extraordinary Results","permalink":"/blog/atomic-habits-summary"}},"content":"## Connection Over Classification\\n\\nWhen you meet new people, your brain naturally tries to label them\u2014where they are from, what they do, or how they look. But these labels are barriers. To truly connect, you must **Drop the Labels**.\\n\\n### 1. Acceptance Without Barriers\\nWe all start as children without biases. As we grow older, we learn to notice differences. But if you walk into a room with an open mind, animals and humans alike will feel the connection immediately. Ego is the wall; love is the bridge.\\n\\n### 2. The 110% Rule\\nGive 110% of your attention when talking to anyone. People remember how you made them feel more than what you said. Everybody fundamentally wants to be heard, respected, and understood.\\n\\n### 3. The Communication Breakdown\\nRemember that communication is far more than just words:\\n*   **7% Words**: What you actually say.\\n*   **38% Tone**: Your inflection and pitch.\\n*   **55% Body Language**: Your face, hands, and posture.\\n\\n### 4. Practical Connection Tips:\\n*   **Simplify Your Language**: Avoid bookish jargon. Good communication is being understood by a 4th grader.\\n*   **Master the 50-70 Rule**: Maintain eye contact for 50-70% of the time to show confidence and interest.\\n*   **Manage Your Pitch**: High pitch shows nervousness; too low can feel aggressive. Find the calm middle ground.\\n*   **Eliminate \\"Failure Words\\"**: Stop using filler words like \\"hmm,\\" \\"obviously,\\" and \\"you know.\\" Silence is better than a filler.\\n\\n#learnings"},{"id":"atomic-habits-summary","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/atomic-habits-summary","editUrl":"https://github.com/yesarpit/yesarpit.github.io/edit/main/blog/2020-12-29-Atomic-Habits-Book-Summary/index.md","source":"@site/blog/2020-12-29-Atomic-Habits-Book-Summary/index.md","title":"Atomic Habits: How Small Changes Lead to Extraordinary Results","description":"Atomic Habits - Small Wins, Compounding Results","date":"2020-12-29T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"book-summary","permalink":"/blog/tags/book-summary"},{"inline":true,"label":"habits","permalink":"/blog/tags/habits"},{"inline":true,"label":"productivity","permalink":"/blog/tags/productivity"}],"readingTime":1.32,"hasTruncateMarker":false,"authors":[{"name":"Arpit Sharma","title":"Maintainer of this blog","url":"https://yesarpit.github.io","imageURL":"https://github.com/yesarpit.png","key":"arpit","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"atomic-habits-summary","title":"Atomic Habits: How Small Changes Lead to Extraordinary Results","authors":["arpit"],"tags":["book-summary","habits","productivity"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Drop the Labels: How to Connect with Anyone","permalink":"/blog/2020/12/30/drop-label-before-you-talk"},"nextItem":{"title":"The 4-Hour Workweek: Escaping the 9-5 Grind","permalink":"/blog/2020/06/05/the-4-hour-workweek-book-summary"}},"content":"## Atomic Habits - Small Wins, Compounding Results\\n\\nJames Clear argues that the quality of our lives depends on the quality of our habits. We don\'t rise to the level of our goals; we fall to the level of our **systems**.\\n\\n### 1. The Power of Compounding\\nA 1% improvement every day makes you 37 times better by the end of the year. This is the **Aggregation of Marginal Gains**. \\n*   Example: The UK cycling team won back-to-back medals after decades of failure by improving everything (seats, tires, even pillows) by just 1%.\\n\\n### 2. Identity-Based Habits\\nMost people focus on *outcomes* (e.g., \\"I want to lose weight\\"). Instead, focus on *identity* (e.g., \\"I am the type of person who never misses a workout\\"). Every action you take is a vote for the person you wish to become.\\n\\n### 3. The 4 Laws of Behavior Change\\nTo build a good habit, follow these laws:\\n1.  **Make it Obvious**: Use \\"Environment Design.\\" If you want to read more, put a book on your pillow.\\n2.  **Make it Attractive**: Use \\"Temptation Bundling.\\" Only watch your favorite show while on the treadmill.\\n3.  **Make it Easy**: Use the **2-Minute Rule**. If a habit takes less than 2 minutes, do it now.\\n4.  **Make it Satisfying**: Use habit tracking to visualize your wins.\\n\\n### 4. The Goldilocks Rule\\nThe human brain loves challenges, but only if they are \\"just right.\\" If a task is too easy, you get bored; if it\'s too hard, you lose motivation. Aim for the zone just outside your comfort.\\n\\n#learnings\\n\\n![Atomic Habits](./atomic-habits-dots.png)"},{"id":"/2020/06/05/the-4-hour-workweek-book-summary","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/2020/06/05/the-4-hour-workweek-book-summary","editUrl":"https://github.com/yesarpit/yesarpit.github.io/edit/main/blog/2020-06-05-the-4-hour-workweek-book-summary.md","source":"@site/blog/2020-06-05-the-4-hour-workweek-book-summary.md","title":"The 4-Hour Workweek: Escaping the 9-5 Grind","description":"The DEAL Formula to Lifestyle Design","date":"2020-06-05T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"book-summary","permalink":"/blog/tags/book-summary"},{"inline":true,"label":"business","permalink":"/blog/tags/business"},{"inline":true,"label":"lifestyle","permalink":"/blog/tags/lifestyle"}],"readingTime":1.09,"hasTruncateMarker":false,"authors":[{"name":"Arpit Sharma","title":"Maintainer of this blog","url":"https://yesarpit.github.io","imageURL":"https://github.com/yesarpit.png","key":"arpit","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"title":"The 4-Hour Workweek: Escaping the 9-5 Grind","authors":"arpit","tags":["book-summary","business","lifestyle"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Atomic Habits: How Small Changes Lead to Extraordinary Results","permalink":"/blog/atomic-habits-summary"},"nextItem":{"title":"Finish: The Practical Guide to Killing Perfectionism","permalink":"/blog/2020/03/21/Finish-Book-Summary"}},"content":"## The DEAL Formula to Lifestyle Design\\n\\nTim Ferriss\u2019s cult classic is about more than just working 4 hours; it\'s about **Lifestyle Design**. The book follows the **DEAL** acronym: **Definition, Elimination, Automation, and Liberation**.\\n\\n### 1. Ask for Forgiveness, Not Permission\\nIf the potential damage is minimal and reversible, don\'t wait for a \\"yes.\\" Waiting for others to guide you is a form of procrastination. Learn by doing, making mistakes, and iterating quickly.\\n\\n### 2. Focus on Strengths, Not Weaknesses\\nMost people spend their lives trying to fix their flaws to become \\"well-rounded.\\" Ferriss argues that multiplier results come from doubling down on your top 3 strengths rather than becoming \\"average\\" at your weaknesses.\\n\\n### 3. Eliminate the \\"Fear of the Void\\"\\nMany people stay in unhappy jobs because they fear the unknown. They expect things will change \\"some day.\\" **Dreamlining** is the antidote\u2014calculating the exact cost of your dreams and realizing that your \\"worst-case scenario\\" is often quite survivable.\\n\\n### 4. The 80/20 Rule (Pareto Principle)\\n80% of your results come from 20% of your activities. \\n*   Identify the 20% of tasks that produce the most value and focus exclusively on them.\\n*   Fire the 20% of clients who cause 80% of your stress.\\n\\n**Conclusion**: Too much money is rarely the answer. The real currency is **Time and Mobility**.\\n\\n#learnings"},{"id":"/2020/03/21/Finish-Book-Summary","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/2020/03/21/Finish-Book-Summary","editUrl":"https://github.com/yesarpit/yesarpit.github.io/edit/main/blog/2020-03-21-Finish-Book-Summary.md","source":"@site/blog/2020-03-21-Finish-Book-Summary.md","title":"Finish: The Practical Guide to Killing Perfectionism","description":"FINISH: Why Done is Better Than Perfect","date":"2020-03-21T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"book-summary","permalink":"/blog/tags/book-summary"},{"inline":true,"label":"productivity","permalink":"/blog/tags/productivity"}],"readingTime":1.29,"hasTruncateMarker":false,"authors":[{"name":"Arpit Sharma","title":"Maintainer of this blog","url":"https://yesarpit.github.io","imageURL":"https://github.com/yesarpit.png","key":"arpit","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Finish: The Practical Guide to Killing Perfectionism","authors":"arpit","tags":["book-summary","productivity"],"type":"Journal"},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"The 4-Hour Workweek: Escaping the 9-5 Grind","permalink":"/blog/2020/06/05/the-4-hour-workweek-book-summary"},"nextItem":{"title":"Crush It! - Turning Passion into a Personal Brand","permalink":"/blog/2019/06/23/crush-it-book-summary"}},"content":"## FINISH: Why Done is Better Than Perfect\\n\\nMost people don\'t have a problem *starting*; they have a problem *finishing*. Jon Acuff argues that our biggest obstacle isn\'t laziness\u2014it\'s **perfectionism**. Here is the blueprint to escape the perfectionism trap:\\n\\n### 1. Cut Your Goal in Half\\nPerfectionism tells you to \\"Go Big or Go Home.\\" Acuff says to cut your goal in half. By making the goal achievable, you take the pressure off and actually build the momentum needed to cross the finish line.\\n\\n### 2. Choose What to Bomb\\nYou cannot be perfect at everything while chasing a new goal. Be intentional about what you are going to let slide (e.g., maybe your house won\'t be as clean while you\'re writing that book). Write a **\\"Not-to-Do\\"** list to stay focused.\\n\\n### 3. Make it Fun if You Want it Done\\nSatisfaction and performance are linked. Identify what motivates you:\\n*   **Reward Motivation**: \\"If I finish this, I get to enjoy a guilt-free movie.\\"\\n*   **Fear Motivation**: \\"If I don\'t finish this, I\'ll have to pay a fine or lose health.\\"\\nUse whichever works for you to keep the process enjoyable.\\n\\n### 4. Leave Your \\"Hiding Places\\"\\nA **Hiding Place** is an activity you focus on *instead* of your goal (e.g., organizing your desk when you should be coding). A **Noble Obstacle** is a rational-sounding excuse (e.g., \\"I can\'t start the YouTube channel because I don\'t have a 4K camera\\"). \\n\\n**The Bottom Line**: Chase progress, not perfection. Publish your \\"Version 1.0\\"\u2014however bad it may be\u2014and then iterate.\\n\\n#learnings"},{"id":"/2019/06/23/crush-it-book-summary","metadata":{"permalink":"/blog/2019/06/23/crush-it-book-summary","editUrl":"https://github.com/yesarpit/yesarpit.github.io/edit/main/blog/2019-06-23-crush-it-book-summary.md","source":"@site/blog/2019-06-23-crush-it-book-summary.md","title":"Crush It! - Turning Passion into a Personal Brand","description":"Crush It: The Art of Personal Branding","date":"2019-06-23T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"book-summary","permalink":"/blog/tags/book-summary"},{"inline":true,"label":"productivity","permalink":"/blog/tags/productivity"},{"inline":true,"label":"branding","permalink":"/blog/tags/branding"}],"readingTime":1.06,"hasTruncateMarker":false,"authors":[{"name":"Gary Vaynerchuk","title":"Original Author","key":"garyv","page":null},{"name":"Arpit Sharma","title":"Maintainer of this blog","url":"https://yesarpit.github.io","imageURL":"https://github.com/yesarpit.png","key":"arpit","page":null}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Crush It! - Turning Passion into a Personal Brand","authors":["garyv","arpit"],"tags":["book-summary","productivity","branding"]},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Finish: The Practical Guide to Killing Perfectionism","permalink":"/blog/2020/03/21/Finish-Book-Summary"}},"content":"## Crush It: The Art of Personal Branding\\n\\nGary Vaynerchuk\u2019s core message is simple: in the digital age, anyone can turn their passion into their profession. But doing so requires more than just interest\u2014it requires turning yourself into a **Personal Brand**. Here are the actionable steps to nail it:\\n\\n### 1. Identify Your Content Medium\\nDon\'t follow the crowd; follow your strengths. If you\'re great on camera, use Video (YouTube/TikTok). If you have a \\"radio face\\" but a great voice, use Audio (Podcasts). If you think more clearly in text, use Writing (Blogs/Twitter). \\n\\n### 2. Document, Don\'t Create\\nGary\u2019s \\"secret sauce\\" is to stop overthinking and start documenting your journey. You don\'t need a high-budget studio; you need authenticity. People connect with the struggle and the process more than the perfected end product.\\n\\n### 3. Hustle and Care\\nHustle is the cost of entry, but \\"caring\\" is the differentiator. You must care about your community more than the money. Reply to every comment, engage with every follower, and build real relationships.\\n\\n### 4. Be Your Own Brand\\nIn the 21st century, your personal brand is your resume. Whether you\'re an employee or a business owner, being known for \\"what you do best\\" is your only survival strategy in an automated world.\\n\\n#learnings"}]}}')}}]);